Subject: Re: RE: [sfraves] speaking of DJ Brian

well, john kelley isn't going to happen because he's booked for the
date we were shooting for.

i've never heard Brian live, but i've been bumping his mixes for the
past year or so.  i love em and would love to book him...but we don't
have any future shows on the horizon that would be a good fit for him.

maybe in the future!

however, if anyone is interested...we do have norcal producer Phokus
playing at our December 16th show.  if you liked Brian's Ritual
Sessions mix, Phokus worked on a few of the tracks on the mix:  Acid
Monsters, Markarian 421 and The Sleeper.

you can check those out on his Myspace:
http://myspace.com/phokusmusic

Phokus is an awesome local producer and we're very happy to have him
joining us on the 16th!

Subject: [sfraves] bsp: Saturday! [KONTROL] @ The Endup w/ The Kooky Scientist + [a]pendics.shuffle - both LIVE!

Saturday, December 2nd

[ K O N T R O L ]

minimal techno + avant house


kicking things off at our new home...
SF's world famous ENDUP!


featuring from Boston:

===== The Kooky Scientist LIVE! =====

Plus 8 . Telepathic . Sub Static . Wax Trax

Boston's Fred Giannelli is about as old school as they come.
>From his early work with Psychic TV, to collaborations with
Richie Hawtin and Dan Bell, to his productions on seminal
dance labels Plus 8 and Wax Trax, this man has seen and
done it all...twice. After hearing his ROCKING live set on the
main stage of this year's D.E.M.F ., we knew we had to bring
this living legend out to prove he hasn't missed a beat.


plus very special guest from Los Angeles:

===== [a]pendics.shuffle LIVE! =====

Adjunct . Mo's Ferry . Orac . Resopal

We brought LA's multi-monikered maestro up last year
and were so impressed we're bringing him back! Expect
no less than dirty, dancefloor-destroying minimal (and
hilarious facial expressions) from the man XLR8R has
called "an American Richard D. James".


resident DJs heating it up early:

ALLAND BYALLO  ( liebe detail . floppy funk )
SAMMY D  ( classic . dirtybird . utensil )
CRAIG KUNA  ( concept sf . esdjco )

THE KOOKY SCIENTIST is perhaps the most well-known of the many aliases
of Boston's legendary Fred Giannelli. Giannelli began experimenting
with electronics in the late '70s as Turning Shrines, but a 1984
meeting with Psychic TV's Genesis P. Orridge at his local radio
station changed his direction. This fateful meeting eventually led to
Giannelli flying to London to join Psychic TV in 1988, arriving just
in time for the Acid House craze. After working with the band for a
few years, including doing the drum programming and production on
1990's classic Towards the Infinite Beat, he gradually separated
himself from Psychic TV and began contributing to the Plus 8 sub-label
Probe, working with Detroit DJs/producers Richie Hawtin and Daniel
Bell as Spawn. Continuing under the Plus 8 banner, he formed the
Telepathic label for his own industrial/techno recordings as the Acid
Didj, Giannelli, Deneuve and Mazdaratti, which are collected on
Telepathic's Telepathic Wisdom, Vol. 1. The 1990's saw him release
some of his most popular titles, including 1992's Fred on famed
industrial label Wax Trax, and 1997's Unpopular Science on Plus 8
under the alias of The Kooky Scientist. Durning this same period and
into the 2000's, he produced remixes for heavy hitters like Steve Bug,
Akufen, and DHS, and his original tracks appeared in DJ mixes by the
likes of John Acquaviva, Stacey Pullen, Adam X, Richie Hawtin and many
more.


Discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Kooky%20Scientist,%20The

2006 (RealAudio stream)
http://www.demf.com/sounds/2006/hmay/05-27-06_kookyscientist_movement06.ram


_________________________________________________


[A]PENDICS.SHUFFLE is but one of many aliases used by LA's electronic
music mastermind Kenneth James Gibson.  Since he first began producing
in 1997, his style has morphed and expanded into a number of different
genres, each released under a different production name (seven to
date, with more on the way!) From the glitchy abstract breaks of Eight
Frozen Modules, to the minimal dubscapes of Dubloner, to the
experimental electro-house of Premature Wig, to his recent Hiss and
Buzz collaboration with electronic pioneer Jack Dangers (Meat Beat
Manifesto, Tino Corp.,) Ken Gibson refuses to be pigeon-holed and is
limited only by his own, seemingly limitless, creativity.   His
consistently exciting and highly prolific output has landed him
releases on such diverse and respected labels as Tigerbeat6, Mille
Plateaux, and Planet Mu, but it is on Seattle 's ORAC where his
four-to-the-floor dancefloor tendencies come out to play as
[a]pendics.shuffle, as evidenced by his latest critically acclaimed
LP, Helicopter Hearts.. With releases also on Matthew "Saftey
Scissors" Curry's Proptronix and his own label Adjunct (which has
featured the likes of Bruno Pronsato, John Tejada, Thomas Jirku and
Pheek,) [a]pendics.shuffle busts out moody, dirty, thumping minimal
techno aimed squarely at the arse,   Recently back in the States after
a yet another European tour, do not miss this opportunity to witness
the man XLR8R magazine has called "an American Richard D. James" in a
very special LIVE performance.


Website (loads of info & music!):
http://www.worldofkennethjamesgibson.com/

discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/%5Ba%5Dpendics.shuffle

[a]pendics.shuffle on MySpace:
http://www.myspace.com/eightfrozenmodules

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Shatter goes techno?


>What exactly does early 90s techno mean to a guy who doesn't play techno 
>normally?


Means I actually like the stuff quite a bit, and even the later years 
techno stuff.  I just never spin it within my circles.

Truthfully, the difference between this and industrial is a few effects and 
synth changes.  Just don't tell the rivetheads that they're listening to 
techno, they get upset.  I can mix amd match all this stuff to any of the 
new industrial tracks with very little effort.  the only thing easy to mix 
is Dancehall.

Oh ya, I'm known for braking out into dancehall tangents.  Might do that 
tonight as well.  Who knows.

Saturday, December 2nd

[ K O N T R O L ]

minimal techno + avant house


kicking things off at our new home...
SF's world famous ENDUP!


featuring from Boston:

===== The Kooky Scientist LIVE! =====

Plus 8 . Telepathic . Sub Static . Wax Trax

Boston's Fred Giannelli is about as old school as they come.
>From his early work with Psychic TV, to collaborations with
Richie Hawtin and Dan Bell, to his productions on seminal
dance labels Plus 8 and Wax Trax, this man has seen and
done it all...twice. After hearing his ROCKING live set on the
main stage of this year's D.E.M.F ., we knew we had to bring
this living legend out to prove he hasn't missed a beat.


plus very special guest from Los Angeles:

===== [a]pendics.shuffle LIVE! =====

Adjunct . Mo's Ferry . Orac . Resopal

We brought LA's multi-monikered maestro up last year
and were so impressed we're bringing him back! Expect
no less than dirty, dancefloor-destroying minimal (and
hilarious facial expressions) from the man XLR8R has
called "an American Richard D. James".


resident DJs heating it up early:

ALLAND BYALLO  ( liebe detail . floppy funk )
SAMMY D  ( classic . dirtybird . utensil )
CRAIG KUNA  ( concept sf . esdjco )
NIKOLA BAYTALA ( robsoul . junior boys own . s.w.a.t. )

____________________________________________________

THE KOOKY SCIENTIST is perhaps the most well-known of the many aliases of
Boston's legendary Fred Giannelli. Giannelli began experimenting with
electronics in the late '70s as Turning Shrines, but a 1984 meeting with
Psychic TV's Genesis P. Orridge at his local radio station changed his
direction. This fateful meeting eventually led to Giannelli flying to London
to join Psychic TV in 1988, arriving just in time for the Acid House craze.
After working with the band for a few years, including doing the drum
programming and production on 1990's classic Towards the Infinite Beat, he
gradually separated himself from Psychic TV and began contributing to the
Plus 8 sub-label Probe, working with Detroit DJs/producers Richie Hawtin and
Daniel Bell as Spawn. Continuing under the Plus 8 banner, he formed the
Telepathic label for his own industrial/techno recordings as the Acid Didj,
Giannelli, Deneuve and Mazdaratti, which are collected on Telepathic's
Telepathic Wisdom, Vol. 1. The 1990's saw him release some of his most
popular titles, including 1992's Fred on famed  industrial label Wax Trax,
and 1997's Unpopular Science on Plus 8 under the alias of The Kooky
Scientist. Durning this same period and into the 2000's, he produced remixes
for heavy hitters like Steve Bug, Akufen, and DHS, and his original tracks
appeared in DJ mixes by the likes of John Acquaviva, Stacey Pullen, Adam X,
Richie Hawtin and many more.


Discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Kooky%20Scientist,%20The

2006 (RealAudio stream)
http://www.demf.com/sounds/2006/hmay/05-27-06_kookyscientist_movement06.ram


_________________________________________________


[A]PENDICS.SHUFFLE is but one of many aliases used by LA's electronic music
mastermind Kenneth James Gibson.  Since he first began producing in 1997,
his style has morphed and expanded into a number of different genres, each
released under a different production name (seven to date, with more on the
way!) From the glitchy abstract breaks of Eight Frozen Modules, to the
minimal dubscapes of Dubloner, to the experimental electro-house of
Premature Wig, to his recent Hiss and Buzz collaboration with electronic
pioneer Jack Dangers (Meat Beat Manifesto, Tino Corp.,) Ken Gibson refuses
to be pigeon-holed and is limited only by his own, seemingly limitless,
creativity.   His consistently exciting and highly prolific output has
landed him releases on such diverse and respected labels as Tigerbeat6,
Mille Plateaux, and Planet Mu, but it is on Seattle 's ORAC where his
four-to-the-floor dancefloor tendencies come out to play as
[a]pendics.shuffle, as evidenced by his latest critically acclaimed LP,
Helicopter Hearts.. With releases also on Matthew "Saftey Scissors" Curry's
Proptronix and his own label Adjunct (which has featured the likes of Bruno
Pronsato, John Tejada, Thomas Jirku and Pheek,) [a]pendics.shuffle busts out
moody, dirty, thumping minimal techno aimed squarely at the arse,   Recently
back in the States after a yet another European tour, do not miss this
opportunity to witness the man XLR8R magazine has called "an American
Richard D. James" in a very special LIVE performance.


Website (loads of info & music!):
http://www.worldofkennethjamesgibson.com/

discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/%5Ba%5Dpendics.shuffle

[a]pendics.shuffle on MySpace:
http://www.myspace.com/eightfrozenmodules

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Djing?

I think we should start djing with 1/4 inch mixtapes and boomboxes. 
Scratching would involve rapid back and forth of the fast forward and 
rewind buttons. You could play with the RPMs by gradually pressing the 
pause button. Tonal control would use those little sliders that always 
fall off the treble and bass. You could mix static from the radio up in 
there. NPR house music will be the next big thing. DJs would take pride 
in their organized tape collection once again.

And the best part is, the more you use the tapes, the muddier the sound!

Obviously vinyl is dead, tapes are the next to come. Revive the mix 
tapes! I need to bust out my walkman again.

-tim

Subject: [sfraves] Jimmy James & Family, an update

To those of you who have seen the news stories about the lost family in
Oregon, James Kim is actually from the Cloud Factory collective here in 
SF/Monterey. If any of you have been to a cloudfactory party from 96-2000, 
chances are you've grooved with Jimmy James.

http://www.jamesandkati.com/

Kati and the kids were found today in good health, after 9 days. The
search intensifies for James who left on foot 2 days ago to find help.

The CF, Oode, and FnF crew lists have blown up with support for our family
member. Just letting you all know since he is relatively close to the SFR
list. Positive thoughts and prayers encouraged for his safe return.

thanks,
-terry

Why waste more tax payers' money in the neoconservatives frankenstein free
market democratic experiment gone wrong?

deployments, bringing troop levels up to around 300,000-500,000 (and then
who know's how long they'll need to stay), and the only way that'll happen
is with a draft.  So really, what's the point?  Given the politics of the
middle east, guerilla warfare, and the shear nearsightedness of the people
pulling the strings for this war, we should've known this was coming-  It
seems as if Bush & Co think we can will this war with nothing more than will
power.

Only bummer was after recommending them strongly at a Harmony crew meeting 
as people we could actually afford that shredded, Brian + Brad didn't 
recognize me despite having talked several times at events down south (I 
used to drive down to LA area for events causee I didn't know anything 
like that up here).

Also, Daniel is the one trance DJ (well, all the Moontribe DJs 
historically were multigenre folk, but Daniel plays trance like few do) 
I'd give a big "doesn't suck" vote to, he folded space and crapped in my 
brainpan and then summoned avatars and shit during a set of his once... 
incredible real energy and talent.  Locally I've only heard Dutch in his 
prime come close.  And it wasn't just that it was trance, it was like 
ridiculously hard psytrance with forays into other hard stuff I think.

Ah, memories of the Elevation parties (the SoCal lists in house kinda 
thing), Moontribe and the old Bud Brothers socials all coming back.  Of 
course, driving back late sunday nights after megafestive weekends in my 
65 mph top speed Suzuki Samurai down I-5 while gulping Red Bull + Ginseng 
+ Water (driving a convertible with a shredded top thru the Central Cali 
night dehydrates the shit out of you) wasn't so good... but I made it 
listening to a bag of old tapes I still have (Moonpup, Deaks, Ethan, DJ 
Dan, Graeme, some classic old shit in there).  :P

In the especially painful department, back in those days I'd have to teach 
class at 8am Monday sharp with 10-15 nerds staring back at me assuming I 
knew something they didn't about computers.  I'm amazed I ever pulled that 
off.

RWDs Guide to House

Wednesday ,6th December 2006

We asked some of the scene's biggest players to break down the who, the what and the why of house in 2006. So if you don't know, now you know... 

Can someone, for the love of God, break down the difference between the 8-million types of house?

"There is only house.   House has been around since the early '80s, it's established and it will always be around.   People may try to sub-categorise it, but it's still just house - the same vibes if it's soulful or funky. I should know - I've been on the scene from the late '80's! I have worked in the studio with Eddie Perez (Smack Production), Roger Sanchez and Erick Morillo." (Booker T) 

Ghetto/ Urban House

"That is a misnomer - a media creation. You may as well call it Black House - it's just house music. You don't hear people call rock music   'white rock' do you?   There no such thing as either ghetto / urban house." (Booker T, MySpace.com/djbookert) 

"I remember Timmi Magic trying to pioneer this one a few years back. The only thing urban about house music is that it has always come from producers and DJs from urban populated areas such as London, New York and Chicago." (DJ Leo, housefm.net and hustlemusic.co.uk) 

Jackin

"Uplifting with a funky groove." (DJ Jolie)

"Now jackin is jackin! Big beats, big bass and a skippy groove, Miami Bass style house." (DJ Leo)
 

Vocal / Soulful

"Soul, jazz, funk influenced with the finishing touch of a diva or male vocal. You can't beat Michelle Weeks, Michael Watford, India or Arnold Jarvis for this!" (DJ Leo) 

Electro / Tech   House

"This style of house is definitely the most popular around the world! When I play in places like Poland or at a Sunday morning afterparty in London they like it dark, deep and dirty. I call it synthesiser music. Bob Moog RIP." (DJ Leo)

CONTINUED:  http://www.rwdmag.com/articles/fullstory.php?&sid=&id=3138




http://www.asambleapopulardeoaxaca.com/ 

MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo 

Tribenet:   <http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k>http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k 
                
House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm

"An adult is one who has lost the grace, the freshness, the innocence of the child, who is no longer capable of feeling pure joy, who makes everything complicated, who spreads suffering everywhere, who is afraid of being happy, and who, because it is easier to bear, has gone back to sleep.  The wise man is a happy child."
-Arnaud Desjardins

"Music rots when it gets too far from the dance.  Poetry atrophies when it gets too far from the music."
-Ezra Pound

The Politics of Fucking
aka 50 Mistakes Women Make When Having Sex

1. Assuming he can get a raging hard on when it suits you. Contrary to popular belief, men can't just flip a switch and get it up because you decided to stop being a frigid bitch. Getting it hard is your job. I suggest you figure it out.

2. Thinking that kissing needs to be this sweet romantic thing all the time. Sometimes pressing your lips against your partners mouth while you get off is the hot. It depends on the situation.

3. Leaving him responsible for your orgasm. You know what gets you off. Tell him. If you don't, it's your own fault when he's snoozing and you're all wound up.

4. Expecting him to cuddle. Men and women are wired differently. Sex makes most women want to talk and bond and all that shit. It makes men pass out. It's a biological thing. Stop fighting it, and stop holding it over his head, it's not his fault.

5. Expecting him to fall asleep with you in his arms. That shit is uncomfortable after awhile. A little snuggling isn't unreasonable, but when it's time to actually sleep? An arm draped over you should suffice.

6. Expecting him to always lay on the charm and romance. Sometimes, that's nice. Sometimes. But expecting him to be all roses and candles all the time is like expecting you to act like a pornstar all the time. If you're not willing to do that, don't expect him to switch for you.

7. Being selfish in bed. Regardless of the shit that Cosmo forces down our throats, sex is NOT just about us. Get over it.

8. Using Cosmo as a sex bible. I dont know who comes up with half that shit, but I'm pretty sure they need counseling.

9. Whining when he pushes your head down on his cock instead of stroking your hair. Know why he's pushing, skippy? Because you aren't doing it right, and have apparently ignored the other clues he's given you. Pay attention to the signals that he's sending you.

10. Not moving at all. Missionary is not an excuse to do nothing.

11. Expecting him to undress himself with any amount of grace. He's about to get some pussy. Be glad he bothered to take his pants all the way off. If it concerns you so much, undress him yourself.

12. Not shaving your legs. Im pretty bad at this myself. But if you want your guy stubble free, you better get out the razor.

13. Allowing your crotch to resemble the amazon. Yes, waxing hurts. Yes, some people don't want to go bare. Thats fine. If you like bush, great. If you have sensitive skin and can't shave, I feel for you. But for the love of Christ, trim that shit if you want him to spend any time down there.

14. Assuming that sex means a relationship. The only relationship you have is that he has now stuck his hoo hoo dilly in your cha cha. That's as far as it goes unless otherwise noted.

15. Withholding oral sex just because you're ragging. He didn't do it. Unless you want him to withhold oral sex because he's hormonal, I suggest you get some kneepads.

16. Expecting him to figure out what you like by what noise you make. Use your words. Have you ever actually heard what you sound like while you're having sex? If you heard yourself on tape, and someone asked you to explain what was causing you to make that noise, 67% of women would respond with answers like "I stubbed my toe" "I ran up the steps" or "I was putting up drywall".

17. Leaving condoms up to him. If you're sexually active and insist that he uses a condom, I suggest buying a box and keeping it by your bed. Not all men keep them on them, and it's just as much your responsibility as it is his. If you think that makes you a slut, you shouldn't be having sex anyway. Go back to Jr High.

18. Getting your undies in a bunch when he talks dirty. A little fantasy can be fun. If he treats you with respect all the time, you shouldn't be offended when he calls you his dirty little slut. When he calls you a whore and tells you to come, its his way of showing that he cares if you get off. Stop being a sissy.

19. Refusing to be spontaneous. I know this is shocking, but sometimes sex OUTSIDE of the bedroom is fun.

20. Dissing quickies because it's not some slow sensual ordeal. Sex is a dynamic thing. Theres an awesome raw energy when you only have 20 minutes but having to have someone so bad that you do it half clothed against the wall. Readjust your thinking.

21. Being too much of a pussy to tell him what is or isn't acceptable before you start bumping uglies. Be honest. If he asks if he can poke you in the butt, and you giggle and say no like it's an invitation, don't look surprised when he "accidentally" sticks his cock in your butt.

22. Expecting him to undress you. I put a bra on almost every day. I know for a fact that getting them off isn't always easy. Help a brother out.

23. Undressing in the dark. If youre shy, dim the lights, but give the man something to see. No ripping off the clothes and diving under the covers, either.

24. Refusing to get on top. Theres no reason men should have to do all the work.

25. Getting that bored look on your face. Men are more visual than women. Give him something to look at. Get on top and arch your back a little bit. Move. Do something to indicate that you 1) are not dead and 2) didn't suffer a minor stroke rendering you unable to move.

26. Expecting him to do all the touching when you're riding him. It's your body, you're used to it. Play with your tits, rub your clit, do something to make his job easier.

27. Being too afraid to guide your partner's hand when hes touching you. Don't like the way he's doing it? Gently take his hand and show him how you like it.

28. Getting into bed, getting naked, fooling around and then deciding that you just want to cuddle, then getting offended when he doesn't. Its your choice to stop, but don't look all fucking surprised when he's confused. You got him naked in your bed, what else did you think was going to happen?

29. Refusing to let him take control. So your a feminist. Big fucking deal. Letting him call the shots doesn't make you any less of one.

30. Refusing to take control. Its ok to crawl across a bed to him on all fours, push him down and crawl on top. It's not his responsibility to start things all the time.

31. Forgetting that he has a body that likes to be touched, too. Men have things like backs and shoulders and stomachs and other parts that are fun to kiss and touch. You miss a lot of good places by concentrating solely on his penis.

32. Ignoring his balls. Seriously, they are there. Kiss them, lick them, suck on them, make a relationship with them, just don't ignore them.

33. Leaving him to his own devices. Nothing is worse than a girl who gets you most of the way off and then bolts because she doesn't want to deal with the mess.

34. Launching into some speech about not being an object for sex when he tries to titty fuck you. Jesus Christ, just push them together and enjoy yourself. You get a great view.

35. Expecting him to handle you like a porcelain doll. I'd hate to be the bearer of bad news, but you're not going to break, sister. So doing it against the wall gives you a bruise on your shoulder. Look at it later and giggle at the memory.

36. Refusing to try things in the name of "making love". You're not making anything. You are naked. With another person. Making strange faces and weird noises. Stop romanticizing it.

37. Taking things way too seriously. Sex is funny. Actually it's hilarious. Somewhere along the line, someone is going to fall off of a bed, hit their head on a lighting fixture, accidentally kick a midget or trip over a goat. It's how you deal with it that really matters.

38. Throwing a bitch fit when he asks for a 3 some. Its the American dream. (I know my ex is reading this right now, so a quick interjection. One request for a 3 some is ok. Every 5 minutes, not so much. Know the difference).

39. Continuing a blow job knowing that you have god awful cotton mouth. Really. Grab a bottle of water.

40. Nails. Its one thing tracing them up and down your partners back. Its another when you snag the goods with a claw.

41. Bitching when you get jizz on you. You're having sex. That will happen. Thats the entire point of sex. Establish where he can and cant jizz and be done with it. Remember, it tightens the pores.

42. Not making any noises at all. Moan. Scream his name. Something so he knows he's the best you've had, even if he isn't.

43. Faking orgasms. Just. Don't. By faking (IF he believes you) he thinks he's doing everything right. And if he doesn't know its not working, he's not going to change it. Starting a vicious cycle of unfulfilling sex which will eventually be very damaging to his ego.

44. Not washing before sex. I know that sex is spontaneous, this is more of a general statement. If you haven't showered that day, and things smell a little...fishy...perhaps demanding oral sex is a little ridiculous of you.

45. Anything that involves inserting anything into his body that he has not specifically approved before hand. I don't care what Cosmo says, some things are simply not pleasant surprises.

46. Refusing to use oils/whipped cream/other messy but fun things because you have 541510630 count Egyptian cotton sheets that were made by hand by the only person alive capable of sewing that pattern. They'll wash.

47. Doing all of your before bed things before sex. Yes, sleeping with makeup on is bad. Now is not the time to remove it, you can do that later. And really fucking you with your hair in a ratty scrunchie with acne cream on your nose is not all its cracked up to be.

48. Cleaning up after sex. Wiping the splooge off is one thing. But changing the sheets immediately so you can get the other ones in the washer and then sanitizing everything your naked body might have possibly passed by is not the way to do it.

49. Making a big deal out of it if he loses his hard on. This is not an interrogation, or 20 questions. It happens, he's probably mortified and you are NOT helping. Refrain from using phrases like "it happens to every guy". Just move to other activities until it gets hard again, and if it doesn't, get off another way with him. He's still capable of getting you off. Mumbling "Forget it" and rolling over are not ok.

50. Asking questions right afterwards. The woman equivalent of "was it good for you?". Now is not a good time to ask "What this means". Right now, it means he probably needs to take a drink, a leak and a nap, perhaps not in that order.

That is all.....

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: oh no's not taco bell...E.Coli outbreaks

you know, there are all kinds of tasty vegetarian options that your
children will love.

morning star makes some really delicious veg breakfast sausage &
meat-like snacks. there are all kinds of gluten-based meat-like
products which are both high in protein and low in fat.

but with all of the chemicals, hormones and other bad shit going into
not only commercial meats, but fruits & vegetables as well, if you are
genuinely concerned I think the easiest thing for you and your
children to do is go for an all-organic diet.

instead of shopping at safeway, shop at your local farmer's market.
you can get organic foods for much cheaper than safeway or whole
foods, and in addition, you are supporting local farmers and
businesses instead of promoting giant corporations. the quaity,
freshness and overall taste of the produce and meat I buy at the
farmers market surpasses that of anything ive ever purchased at a
major grocery store, including whole foods.

organic foods may not be lower in fat but they are certainly
healthier, more nutritious and better for you and your family in the
long run. that way you dont need to cut out the chicken, just buy free
range organic chicken. it tastes better, too!

just my .02

Subject: [sfraves] Question to DJ's/Promoters

Just a general question for y'all out there...

What is your perspective regarding DJ's promoting events they are at?

What I mean to ask is - if you were booked at an event (or if you are a 
promoter, if you book DJ's at your event), do you think the DJ's should do 
promotion, and do you think it's respectful for them to include the full 
lineup of the party?

I personally ALWAYS promote for events I play at, and always include the 
names of everyone on the lineup. I'm just wondering what other peoples 
thoughts on the subject are....

Discuss...

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Question to DJ's/Promoters


I think part of a DJ's pay should be for assisting to promote.

I mean, why book a DJ that nobody is going to come out to hear?  If they 
don't have their own fan base, or at least friend network, then why have 
them spin unless you just want somebody for filler sound.  If that's the 
case, why would you even mention that you have a DJ?

If a DJ wants repeat bookings, IMHO, then they better be able to pull a 
crowd..   especially in the bay area..  where as I've said..  throw a rock 
and you'll hit 12 DJ's.

> children to do is go for an all-organic diet.
>

> you can get organic foods for much cheaper than safeway or whole
> foods, and in addition, you are supporting local farmers and
> businesses instead of promoting giant corporations. the quaity,
> freshness and overall taste of the produce and meat I buy at the
> farmers market surpasses that of anything ive ever purchased at a
> major grocery store, including whole foods.
>
> organic foods may not be lower in fat but they are certainly
> healthier, more nutritious and better for you and your family in the
> long run. that way you dont need to cut out the chicken, just buy free
> range organic chicken. it tastes better, too!

I generally will promote events I am playing online. I try to include the c=
omplete lineup but in the days of 50 djs an event that can sometimes be a b=
it of an overload. I almost never promote by flyer these days. I have deep =
rooted beliefs that a good event production includes a strong marketing/pro=
motion team. A dj is just that a dj they are hopefully either playing event=
s and building their dj portfolio or they are still new enough and are home=
 practicing. Event producers are booking djs for their music (hopefully) an=
d not for their ability to promote a show. Here in Portland there are sever=
al event producers that depend on djs promoting their shows for success rat=
her than hard work. I love to spin events and will do my best to get the wo=
rd out digitally but I won't take time away from my family to promote an ev=
ent. I won't bring stacks of flyers from the different shows I am playing t=
o my current gigs, it is a hassle and the people I am playing for would rat=
her I focus on the event I am playing at that moment.=20
=20
Lots of opinions. Maybe I am just the asshole who knows.=20
=20

Reason I asked is because a local DJ who apparently thinks of themselves as 
a world class headliner feels that it's not their position to either promote 
an event they're at or give credit to the other DJ's on a lineup. We got in 
a bit of a debate about it, and I just wanted to see what general consensus 
was...

--0-650162595-1165602874=:91909
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=iso-8859-1
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit

i'll promote to some degree for every party i play at, whether it's online or by handing out hard copy flyers. since most flyers and BSPs include all of the DJs at the party, the full lineup is normally represented by default. 

i have to admit though, my online promotion (posting to lists, etc.) is a lot more egalitarian than my street promotions. when i hand out flyers on the streets/at parties (love parade, etc.), i pretty much look for the hottest guys i can find, start talking to them about the party, and hand them a flyer if they seem even remotely cool.

i fully expect every DJ i book to help spread the word about the party too. i would think that would kind of go without saying... and for the performers i'd be comfortable adding to a lineup, it totally would. the people i work with understand that throwing a successful party is a group effort.

to be honest, i'm surprised this is actually an issue.

love,
mo

Van Mundegaarde <electrofunk138@hotmail.com> wrote: Just a general question for y'all out there...

What is your perspective regarding DJ's promoting events they are at?

What I mean to ask is - if you were booked at an event (or if you are a 
promoter, if you book DJ's at your event), do you think the DJ's should do 
promotion, and do you think it's respectful for them to include the full 
lineup of the party?

I personally ALWAYS promote for events I play at, and always include the 
names of everyone on the lineup. I'm just wondering what other peoples 
thoughts on the subject are....

Discuss...

Subject: RE: [sfraves] Question to DJ's/Promoters


IMHO, you're pinging almost dead on.

When I DJ, I always put out some online blubage. If I have fliers, I put'em 
out if I'm somewhere and don't see any.  I'm not stading outside hammering 
everyone walking out of the place.  If I'm there I'll mention it to people 
I know, etc.  Remind'em "Hey, I'm spinning this friday, come by and say hi 
if you're out and about..."  etc.

When I'm promoter It's pretty much what I ask of peopel DJ'ing for me.  Not 
to carry the weight of the event, but suppliment.  Let your friends know, 
throw out an online reminder or two, and keep a few fliers in your bag 
incase you're talking to somebody and they hadn't heard.

since im not at work,i can actually type this

the law firm i work for specializes in helping corporations bend the
law to their will. To give you a taste of their clients, they include:

Microsoft
clear channel
Cartier and many other jewelers
GM
Nike
Tyco
Viacom
Sony
etc...

they specialize in helping these businesses work outside of the
borders and within the borders of the US and they are INSANE with
contractual law. Like say the US brings a suit against MS for monopoly
practices. Not only will this firm make it look like MS is the
underdog on paper, but they can also shuffle influence around within
the house and senate to get the hearings either railroaded or to be
exactly what they were meant to be: a public show for the people to
help the senators and congressmen earn votes. To be honest, if it
wasn't for the pro-bono work the attorneys do( transgendered rights,
Homosexual rights, helping homeless people or impoverished people with
free legal help(i.e. helping them get businesses started, etc.) and
child protection law to name a few) i'd have quit out of disgust, but
unfortunately, firms like that need to exist because in an odd way,
they may help corporations skirt the law, but they do keep the wheels
of industry running...it may seem sinister, but they kind of keep
things in balance.

oh, and as far as organic food, that is ALL you should eat(if
possible). Infact, all foods should be unprepared/unpackaged for
maximum health. If eating properly, one could get the body brad pitt
had in fight club without hard core exercise. I know with just
flipping up my eating habits, i've gone from 270 pounds to 245, should
be at 215(what would be 6-8% body fat for me) by spring/summer. Also,
when eating better, i seriously feel 100% better than when shoving
preservatives and the like in to my body. Would have never noticed had
it not been for the french and their lack of any preservatives in
their food...fresh cut steak is fucking delicious and doesn't make you
feel full and nasty.

speaking of which, anyone know of a good organic butcher in SF? We
have one here in DC, and i am definitely going to miss it.

On 8 December 2006, Nathan Seven wrote:

> On Dec 8, 2006, at 6:50 PM, J.C. wrote:
>
>> That's truly up for debate. :)  For example, corporations tend to be amoral 
>> toward the law.  If it's cost effective, they obey it.  So, if a 
>> corporation believes that it may get caught and fined for breaking some 
>> regulation, but it's less than the cost of complying with that regulation, 
>> what do you suppose they will do?  Would that be considered an evil act?
>
> ???
>
> People do this every day.
> They weigh the consequences of illegal actions and decide whether to do them 
> or not.
>
> Ever done any drugs?
> Ever been speeding on the highway?
>
> Yeah...

In the example cases, it's generally oneself that's going to be harmed 
should anything go wrong.  In the case of corporations, it's generally 
others that end up dead as a result.

hella made me think of silent hill... I expected Pyramid Head to be
lurking around a corner. What was that place, an old daycare center??

rolling out, some rent-a-cops asked us, "Hey, where are all of you
coming from?"

I miss this kind of shit soooo bad. The cutty spots, the occasional
flight from security personell... Its really too bad ,most of the kids
care about is a "safe and secure venue" where there's no chance of
their roll being interrupted. This kind of shit is essential to the
rave experience, goddamnit.

Hell, lots of people actually LIVE out here on Treasure Island, so  
it's not like they could just block off the road and nab all the  
ravers without harassing tons of local mundnes who'd raise hell.   
Also, MUNI runs 24/7 out here too; and if you hide all the candy and  
blinky shit under your jacket or hoodie, you look like any other late- 
night bus-riding crazy.

Hearing about this party actually kind of annoys me... 'cuz I was  
just hanging out not doing much of anything last night; and if I'd  
hared about the party in time I could have WALKED there and back.

But yeah, there are hella parts of the old navy base out here that  
are sitting totally empty and unused that'd make for great renegade  
venues for a promoter that was ballsy enough to take the chance and  
quick and witty enough to get people in and out without attracting  
attention.

Vinyl singles making a comeback in Britain

By Lars Brandle 2 hours, 43 minutes ago

LONDON (Billboard) - Physical singles may be losing the war against  
digital formats, but the U.K. market has found an unlikely hero to  
lead the fight: good, old-fashioned, 7-inch vinyl.

Fueled predominantly by independent labels and alternative groups  
like Arctic Monkeys and Kaiser Chiefs, the format -- also known as a  
45 in its pre-'90s heyday -- is experiencing a mini-revival in the  
United Kingdom. In recent years, labels have increasingly added  
limited edition versions of 7-inch singles to their armory, which are  
targeted at "indie" rock consumers as trendy collectibles.

CONTINUED:  http://news.yahoo.com/s/nm/20061211/music_nm/britain_dc_3




apollo@speakeasy.org

MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo

Tribenet:   http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k

Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm



"No sage or savior has ever endorsed greed and gluttony as a path  
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and  
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras,  
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and  
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can  
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and  
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond  
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative  
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in  
squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of  
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will  
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

<StartStrangeSideTopic>

I break the law on a daily basis (speeding), but not once in 14 years have I
ever harmed anyone because of it. Is it moral, yes, because I do not believe
speed has anything to do with accidents. Not sure what this has to do with
anything, but speed laws annoy me. The real issue is paying attention and
driving correctly for conditions.

</StartStrangeSideTopic>

the free drinks).

good time.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] club contacts sought

That sort of shadiness is one of the reasons I still keep my PO BOX  
as my primary mailing address, even though I've lived in one  
apartment for so long, now, that it's really not justified for its  
original purpose.

I once had the shadiest of the shady of the rave promoters I ever  
knew openly admit to me that he used the things not because he cared  
about underage drinking (He always had a 21+ area with additional,  
more through, scrutiny on IDs; or didn't have alcohol at all.), but  
so he could build up his junk mail list.  And indeed, the only time  
I've ever actually gotten rave flyers as junk mail, were from parties  
in which he was involved, and I had my license scanned.

After that, If I knew he was involved in the party, but I had somehow  
gotten myself obligated to go anyway, I would use my passport  
instead.  You can't scan my address if there's no magstripe... and no  
address.

I guess I shouldn't be surprised that the things have become the rage  
at clubs too...  If I ever wind up giving up parties and going back  
to clubs instead, I guess I'll have to remember to bring the passport  
along to those as well...


cya,
john

Subject: Re: [sfraves] club contacts sought


I havn't seen that Biobouncer yet, but I think I really like it.

The biggest problem with security is when you get rid of a shitbag, and 
have a shift change, it's hard to know they were tossed.  Sure, you can 
photocopy the iD, but how do you rememeber a years worth of who's you don't 
want around, and who's ok.  How do you tell somebody to stay away for a 
month, and make sure it's enforced?

I know there's two types of scanners...  Verification and 
Telemetry.  You're all familiar with the second, the first just lets you 
know if the data on the stripe is real.  You can recode them to fool some 
readers, but the good ones are supposed to match up to a checksum bit or 
other verification.  Not sure but it's a simple green light/red light.

There are some other advantages to them I've looked into.  Take this whole 
thing form a different persepctive..  a positive one:

Instead of worrying about who you want to keep out, how about those you 
always want in? VIP cards are great and all, but how about just putting 
somebody ona  house list?  Or free before midnight?  What about one persn 
in free before 11pm and the guy behind them is all night?  Reading those 
lists and rememebering is a pain.  Maybe somebody is suppose dto get a few 
drink tickets when they come by?  How about DJ's who have an open guest 
list, but the ticket take doesn't always know who they are?

Well, there is software you can run that will do that for you as 
well.  Sure, you can flag the dirtballs to get DO NOT ADMIT, but at the 
same time you can also find out about the cool people.  It saves time of 
pouring over  aguest list, argueing, looking agin, etc etc.  They can speed 
your line up drastically which is good for everyone.  People don't want to 
wait outside, DJ's don't want an empty club, and bars want revenue.

>
> IMHO, you're pinging almost dead on.

> When I DJ, I always put out some online blubage. If I have fliers, I 
> put'em out if I'm somewhere and don't see any.  I'm not stading outside 
> hammering everyone walking out of the place.  If I'm there I'll mention it 
> to people I know, etc.  Remind'em "Hey, I'm spinning this friday, come by 
> and say hi if you're out and about..."  etc.
>
> When I'm promoter It's pretty much what I ask of peopel DJ'ing for me. 
> Not to carry the weight of the event, but suppliment.  Let your friends 
> know, throw out an online reminder or two, and keep a few fliers in your 
> bag incase you're talking to somebody and they hadn't heard.
>
>
> At 08:44 AM 12/8/2006, Jason Philips wrote:
>>I generally will promote events I am playing online. I try to include the 
>>complete lineup but in the days of 50 djs an event that can sometimes be a 
>>bit of an overload. I almost never promote by flyer these days. I have 
>>deep rooted beliefs that a good event production includes a strong 
>>marketing/promotion team. A dj is just that a dj they are hopefully either 
>>playing events and building their dj portfolio or they are still new 
>>enough and are home practicing. Event producers are booking djs for their 
>>music (hopefully) and not for their ability to promote a show. Here in 
>>Portland there are several event producers that depend on djs promoting 
>>their shows for success rather than hard work. I love to spin events and 
>>will do my best to get the word out digitally but I won't take time away 
>>from my family to promote an event. I won't bring stacks of flyers from 
>>the different shows I am playing to my current gigs, it is a hassle and 
>>the people I am playing for would rather I focus on the event I am playing 
>>at that moment.
>>
>>Lots of opinions. Maybe I am just the asshole who knows.

On Mon, 11 Dec 2006, Shatter wrote:
-&e->I havn't seen that Biobouncer yet, but I think I really like it.
-&e->
-&e->The biggest problem with security is when you get rid of a shitbag, and
-&e->have a shift change, it's hard to know they were tossed.  Sure, you can
-&e->photocopy the iD, but how do you rememeber a years worth of who's you don't
-&e->want around, and who's ok.  How do you tell somebody to stay away for a
-&e->month, and make sure it's enforced?

Another upside to biobouncer, and id scanning...

I'll never come to your club!  Woohoo!

We DESERVE the right to anonymity.  In the big city, if I can't see you, 
you have no fucking right to know any more about me than you already get.  
Don't be a sheep, you should be reluctant to give your CA DL, SSID, credit 
cards, etc.  Too much data already tying together on simple primary keys, 
profiling databases exist, and there's plenty of people whose life it is 
to connect the dots over and over again till its a nice predictable 
statistical meadow you can bleat in to your heart's content.

andyw

p.s.  I'm not pro-shooter or anti-bouncer, I'm just pro civil liberties 
and understand the issues that come with privacy in the digital age.  
There is a lot of room between not being comfortable making it really easy 
to tie your purchasing habits, call records, leisure activities, taste in 
films, etc together... and being full blown paranoid.  I'm not even so 
worried about the NSA, at least they have policies on how to store and use 
data like that.  But some club promoter potentially having access in one 
night to my credit card number, driver's license, my image, etc and 
storing it in some "my first POS & bouncer app 4 windoze" with an Access 
backend that is stored to unencrypted CD-R backups and left in normal 
trash a couple weeks down the road?  No fucking way.

privacy spaz -----------o--- full blown paranoid

andyw - mutorsoundsystem - saturn5.com/andy

Looks like these are removable, and there's a lot of fonts available, but they look kind of expensive too:
   
  http://www.craftcuts.com/wall-letters.html
   
  Wall Letters 
  wall words / wall letters / vinyl letter  CraftCuts.com offers vinyl lettering wall words for your wall home decor. These vinyl letters are self adhesive (stick on vinyl lettering) wall letters, decorative letters or vinyl wall words. Vinyl lettering for decorating walls is an easy way of adding nursery wall letters, decorative lettering or decorative wall letters to your home, baby, or kids room. Each wall letter is available on craft boards and as custom vinyl window lettering (decals). Wall lettering is simple, just press the custom decorative wall letters on and the decorative wall word saying will stay until you want to take it off. All vinyl letter decorative lettering comes in each alphabet wall letter and number. See our quote and phrase custom wall lettering gallery for examples of custom wall vinyl letters. Over 1,700 alphabet decorative letter fonts are available in 16 different colors. If you own a retail store or online shop and are interested in wholesale
 vinyl lettering, wall letters, and decorative letters please contact us for wholesale pricing.

If you have a printer how about using sticker paper and just printing them
out yourself? Then you can choose the font and look. People always trip out
when I show them stickers I made using my computer. It's such an obvious
thing to do, but people forget about doing it.

Well that's why I asked this question here.  Personally I don't think the c=
lubbing application is an obvious winner for some of the reasons you've out=
lined.  But the technology exists and therefore will likely be used somewhe=
re.=0A=0AI think there are settings where we already accept and expect that=
 our identity is going to be verified and we are generally OK with that.  F=
or example, in a bank when you try to withdraw funds from an account.  Anot=
her example, we usually expect people who we work with to openly and honest=
ly identify themselves. So the question is really about when and where to r=
equire positive identification.  Obviously there are some places where we n=
ormally expect to identify ourselves and learn the identities of others.  I=
n other situations the level of identification required and our expectation=
s of that are much lower.  =0A =0AYou can't enter most clubs today without =
presenting some form of identification.  Even some "raves" require ID to be=
 presented.  There's really nothing stopping a promoter from capturing or d=
atabasing your license information even without a scanner.  Its just much e=
asier with the scanner.  And of course if you use a credit card your transa=
ctions are already traceable.  Your presence at the club isn't much of a se=
cret if you charge that bottle on your AMEX card.  And its not unusual to b=
e asked for ID when charging things either.  Even cash transactions can be =
traced in some cases; serial numbers of some denominations of cash are reco=
rded when they are put in the teller's cash drawer or ATM and then again wh=
en they are deposited.  Inferences can be made about transaction pathways f=
rom examinaiton of databases of large numbers of transactions.=0A =0AFWIW, =
IMO, the days where you can assume any anonymity in any public space includ=
ing at a rave or club are simply over.  There are just too many cameras out=
 there, too many recording devices, too many nosy people.  Almost everyone =
has a camera in their pocket now.  I have two actually.  And our data trail=
s are too valuable not be collected and mined by corporations.=0A=0AToday i=
f you want to be anonymous, you are going to have to spend some time, money=
, and intellectual effort to do it.  It will require hard work.  Otherwise =
you are just playing around and pretending to be anonymous as some sort of =
political statement.  If you really needed to avoid being imaged or recogni=
zed by a state of the art surveillance system could you even do it?  I can =
tell you for a fact that most people couldn't and it is getting much harder=
 to avoid or evade these systems as time goes on.=0A =0AIt also depends who=
 you trying to remain anonymous from.  The NSA?  The press?  An ex-wife?  Y=
our employer?  A secret new world order conspiracy?  Different approaches a=
nd counter measures are required in each of these cases.=0A=0AEver hear of =
David Brin's book *The Transparent Society*?  The real question now is who =
gets to control this technology.  =0A =0APeace,=0A=0APeter=0A=0A----- Origi=

Subject: Re: [sfraves] club contacts sought

No Tin Foil Hat here.

I once let my ID get scanned at a club by some cigarette promo dude. I 
got a free zippo out of the deal. Now Camel cigarettes mails to my house 
a birthday present every year right before my birthday. With my name on 
it. With coupons. Personalized to me. That was after ONE incident of 
allowing my ID to get scanned. I'm in a database somewhere with my 
address, birthdate, what kind of car I drive, my age and even picture. 
Now, knowing a club can potentially have the same sort of access, and 
even more? No way.

I really don't want to receive discounts sent to my house on whips and 
chains for that one BDSM club I visited way back when. Or anyone to know 
that I sometimes listen to 80's, or what books I check out at the library.

I can expect to be on camera at a club. That's an incidental effect of 
being at a large venue. A camera has no prejudice with the images it 
takes. But mandatory ID scanning prior to entry is a proactive targeting 
of customers. With that sort of power, I expect bills to be written, 
handbooks to be circulated to all patrons, a regulatory constitution to 
be voted on by an elected body, otherwise it's a no-go.

Being in the name of "safety" is one of the dumbest fucking arguments 
I've ever heard. That's how we all got the Patriot Act. And I don't see 
you all jumping up and down in defense of that.

-t

Subject: Re: [sfraves] club contacts sought


I actually agree with the whole "by allowing us to scan your ID you 
willfull agree to get all our mailing list crap."

btw-  The cig people have an opt out on their web site so you won't recieve 
their stuff.

If I were working at a club that did the ID scanning or instituted it, I 
would insist that they have the terms CLEARLY posted for everyone to read, 
and if they did any form of data collection for reasons of any form of 
promotion without consent I would be rather annoyed.

Like I said, there are two types, the data collector and the verification only.

The one thing most people who havn't worked in bars and clubs (venue level) 
is that the California ABC have the most insnae set of draconian facists 
laws regarding alchohol sales.  Every step of the way you are damned if you 
do, damned if you don't.

eg:  You have a medical problem and call a paramedic.  You are REQUIRED to 
do so.  Failure to do so can result in losing your licence.   If you have 
TOO MANY of these calls, they will pull your licence.

You are required to ID every person walking into the bar, regardless of 
age.  There is no clause about "If you look over 30" liek they have in the 
grocery stores.  All peopel entering teh building, at all times, every 
time.  The rules get bent with hand stamps, but to be perfectlly by the 
letter of the law you should card somebody everytime they walk in, even if 
you've seen it 1000x.

Now, ABC does have some aspects like "Best Effort".   What that means is 
that if something happens, they won't fine you AS BAD.  Oh they'll fine 
you, but maybe it'll only be $15,000 instead of $50,000 for letting in 
somebody with a fake ID.

This is what the scanners, cameras, additional security and such are all 
for.  Promoters have a far more vested interest in your personal 
information.  Clubs really only have all this crap in place just so if 
something happens they can say "We did the best we could" in front of the 
judge, and to get better insurance premiums.

As far as safety, I agree with you.  I'm pretty big on safety being a 
personal responsibility.  I'll handle my own, thank you.  Typically in a 
club the term safety isn't regarding individuals, but more of the alcohol 
licence.  Everyone get's to jump through all these hoops so we can listen 
to our friends play music and get drunk at night.

Mime-Version: 1.0

X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR - Non-permanent letters for decorations

as a former painter, I highly recommend staying away from the tacky 
stuff.  If you leave it up for any long amount of time, it bonds to 
the wall / paint.  Removal is possible, but repainting is necessary 
afterwards.  I had to clean a ton of that stuff off of walls in a 
sorority house in Berkeley.

Blue tape is much, much safer for paint.  They're both 3M products, 
you'd think they could do both well...


sarilion

Subject: Re: [sfraves] club contacts sought

You're re-directing the argument. The argument is about using ID 
scanners to admit entry into clubs.

I wouldn't be okay with mandatory ID scannings for Target shoppers, 
either. I think they can come up with the same pro arguments: "To keep 
the bad elements out.","To give coupons and discounts directly to the 
consumer instead of wasting paper via mailings","For the benefits of 
understanding buying habits". Doesn't mean they're good arguments, or 
that we should allow them to get away with it without questioning their 
authority every step of the way. They have security cameras and security 
personnel, too, which I live with. And so what, even if I choose to use 
a credit card at Target that can track my buying habits, I have the 
OPTION of instead choosing to pay by using untraceable cash.

As a happy medium, why don't be really cutting edge and install 
updateable RFID tags onto the bottoms of all drinking cups and 
containers? That way we can figure out exactly which shadowy areas of 
the venue drinkers prefer, and, you know, market to them. I bet you 
could get funding for that project, and it would be fun to implement as 
it would be an entirely closed system. Would look a bit like Digg Swarm, 
i think.

And yeah, I know a bit about those facial recognition camera systems. I 
worked with a few on a basic level for art installations.

-t

-Okay i'm out... no more NRR for a while ;)


dangrsmind@yahoo.com wrote:
> "A camera has no prejudice with the images it takes."
>
> This isn't really true.  In the context of a large venue's security system you usually have people monitoring at least some of the cameras and deciding when to intervene in various situations.  Since humans are involved there are clearly biases.  And some cameras are steerable or can be zoomed on specific areas by these personnel.  Clubs also use hidden cameras unlike other heavily imaged places like banks.  Selective placement of hidden cameras can be a form of prejudice.
>
> It is also not true that you can't be identified and tracked if you don't submit to an ID scan.  When the camera is connected to a facial recognition system the club might not know your true name, but they can still track you anonymously.  Existing systems allow the club to record when you visit, what areas of the club you prefer, potentially determine other people who you talk with, and more.  This information has value to the venue owner both for security and marketing purposes, and you can expect them to extract that value when it is economically feasible and in their interest to do so.  
>
> Simply by using a well placed camera and time stamp information a venue owner can link your face with a list of credit card transactions that also are time stamped.  This can all be done covertly without your cooperation or knowledge.  These features are increasingly being built into security oriented DVR (digital video recorder) platforms so they will be standard capabilities of many surveillance systems in a few years.  See for example: http://www.3vr.com
>
> And it isn't just the venue owner.  Phones are being built that have face recognition capability built in, and there are services emerging that are going to offer various sorts of image search and analytics to the consumer directly on their PCs and mobile devices.  
>
> See also: http://www.applefritter.com/bannedbooks
>
> Like i said previously, remaining anonymous today takes work. It is no longer a given.
>
> Regards,
>
> Peter
>
>
>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] club contacts sought


Wow...   ya, this is going REAL far off the original topic...  I'm actually 
finding his stimulating considering various projects I've been involved 
with in the past.  The comical ironic side is a lot of this is so passe 
that seeing it here would be like reader of SFR stumbling across a 
discussion on another list about "these new underground all night parties 
and their use of ectasy combined with pusation techno music and glowsticks" 
being something new and unheard of.

First off...  I don't know of any club that monitors the cameras 
actively.  Most go to a DVR system or...  in older cases, still to 
VHS.  You might have a manager watching something at random points, however 
typically, they are reviewed as needed, typically based on security logs, 
incident reports, or other issues.  I can also say that 99% of the time, 
they are view to make sure employee'd acted correctly, and not to keep tabs 
on a particular patron.  There are time that if somebody was a problem, eg 
weapon in club, the tapes will be played back to find out what time they 
entere dthe club, who was on door, to find out who fucked up on the 
screening/pat down.

In all cases I've dealt with security footage, it's been in conjunction 
with a report, to gain a different viewpoint, or see what was missed.  I've 
never had a time where the footage was watched looking for something 
happening at the time, live.  They're always watched at a later time, be it 
an hour or several weeks later.

Clubs I work in, if they even have inside cameras, they are typically on 
the bar and the registerers, and are used to make sure employee's arn't 
robbing the place.  They are also on various access points, such as 
emergancy doors, back access hallways, and such.  Because of the way they 
record, and the nightclub enviorment, recording inside a club would be 
somewhat problematic.  Don't believe me?  Feel free to tune into DNA's 
webcam live anytime you like:   Http://www.dnalounge.com  Watch for a while 
and you'll see that the crowd shots are next to impossibleto make out who's 
who.  The stage is easy enough of the lights are brough.  The bar isn't bad 
only because of constant illumination, and the front door is the easiest to 
watch.  Friends of mine in Portland have had many entertaining nights with 
beer and a computer, watching the front door camera, adding their own 
soundtrack to what they see.

Again, nightclubs are not casinos.

Now....  since this has diverted, and RFID's have been brought 
up...  consider this:

Stores have talked about, and have already implimented things such as RFID 
dust.  When you walk in you get hit with teh dust.  This tells scanners any 
number of bits of data.  If it's incrimented with a sequential number say 
every 5 minutes, they know when you enter and leave a store.  As you walk 
around in the store, they can track movements, and see what people are 
looking for, when you browse, stop, etc.  They have talked about things 
such as active coupons and sale deals, that when you walk up, your RFID is 
read and sales are brought to your attention, to the extent that they read 
what you have already put in your basket, and make reccomendations as you 
shop around.  Hows that for Big Brother?

Years back...   '93/'94 I'd have to say, I was on a voice brdige and 
somebdoy was pulling various pranks.  We called up Gail Thackery just for 
fun (see Operation Sundevil in your cyber history books).  She pointed out 
back that far that if what we had thought was bad then was nothing 
comapired to what we would be seeing with the "Club Cards" and membership 
cards like Costco.  Imagine your every item purchased front food, to 
alcohol, tobacco, foot cream, antacid, pain killers, cigarettes, etc., 
going into variousdata bases.  Not anon shopping patterns, but right down 
to all of your personal information and Social Security number.

Now, take that one step further and tie that into your credit and medical 
history.   Imagine getting a letter from your HMO saying that they are 
raising your preimiums because you have moved into a new class of at risk 
for heart disese based on the amount of red meat you've been purchasing 
over the last several years, or you are now being screened for a possible 
addition to decongestants because you have purchased more than is safe to 
use in a given time frame.  Perhaps you are ot given a job offer because 
when looking over your candidate sceening report they saw that you are an 
above average consumer of alcohol and their insuance won't cover alcoholics.

In light of these various things....   showing ID at a bar seems pretty 
trivial.



At 08:26 PM 12/12/2006, tbSMITH wrote:
>You're re-directing the argument. The argument is about using ID scanners 
>to admit entry into clubs.
>
>I wouldn't be okay with mandatory ID scannings for Target shoppers, 
>either. I think they can come up with the same pro arguments: "To keep the 
>bad elements out.","To give coupons and discounts directly to the consumer 
>instead of wasting paper via mailings","For the benefits of understanding 
>buying habits". Doesn't mean they're good arguments, or that we should 
>allow them to get away with it without questioning their authority every 
>step of the way. They have security cameras and security personnel, too, 
>which I live with. And so what, even if I choose to use a credit card at 
>Target that can track my buying habits, I have the OPTION of instead 
>choosing to pay by using untraceable cash.
>
>As a happy medium, why don't be really cutting edge and install updateable 
>RFID tags onto the bottoms of all drinking cups and containers? That way 
>we can figure out exactly which shadowy areas of the venue drinkers 
>prefer, and, you know, market to them. I bet you could get funding for 
>that project, and it would be fun to implement as it would be an entirely 
>closed system. Would look a bit like Digg Swarm, i think.

>dangrsmind@yahoo.com wrote:
>>"A camera has no prejudice with the images it takes."
>>
>>This isn't really true.  In the context of a large venue's security 
>>system you usually have people monitoring at least some of the cameras 
>>and deciding when to intervene in various situations.  Since humans are 
>>involved there are clearly biases.  And some cameras are steerable or can 
>>be zoomed on specific areas by these personnel.  Clubs also use hidden 
>>cameras unlike other heavily imaged places like banks.  Selective 
>>placement of hidden cameras can be a form of prejudice.
>>
>>It is also not true that you can't be identified and tracked if you don't 
>>submit to an ID scan.  When the camera is connected to a facial 
>>recognition system the club might not know your true name, but they can 
>>still track you anonymously.  Existing systems allow the club to record 
>>when you visit, what areas of the club you prefer, potentially determine 
>>other people who you talk with, and more.  This information has value to 
>>the venue owner both for security and marketing purposes, and you can 
>>expect them to extract that value when it is economically feasible and in 
>>their interest to do so.
>>
>>Simply by using a well placed camera and time stamp information a venue 
>>owner can link your face with a list of credit card transactions that 
>>also are time stamped.  This can all be done covertly without your 
>>cooperation or knowledge.  These features are increasingly being built 
>>into security oriented DVR (digital video recorder) platforms so they 
>>will be standard capabilities of many surveillance systems in a few 
>>years.  See for example: http://www.3vr.com
>>
>>And it isn't just the venue owner.  Phones are being built that have face 
>>recognition capability built in, and there are services emerging that are 
>>going to offer various sorts of image search and analytics to the 
>>consumer directly on their PCs and mobile devices.
>>
>>See also: http://www.applefritter.com/bannedbooks
>>
>>Like i said previously, remaining anonymous today takes work. It is no 
>>longer a given.
>>
>>Regards,
>>
>>Peter

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR - Non-permanent letters for decorations


I shop there all the time.

While it isn't free, for the amount I've gotten there, it might as well 
be.  18 full bolts of fabric that would normally go for $3/yd for a grand 
total of $90.

They have the normal foam core as well as the larger stuff liek 
1inch.  They get the olde trade show signs that are huge that said "M - S" 
for registration.  I think I saw a full one (3x8 feet) for $12.  Used once, 
then tossed.

They have a lot of fabric on the roll, paper, textile, wood, metal, glass, 
hardware (eg a 20 gal tub full of new brass belt buckles), old magazines, 
fileing cabnets with new patterns (60's and 70's clothing no less - who 
needs a Pantsuit?) candles, paints, unexposed film, boxes of discarded 
photographs, vinal records, carpet, floor time, etc etc etc.  Pennies on 
teh dollar at best.  Not much is actually priced.  Pretty much get 
everything together, take it up to the counter.  They eye it, roll it 
around, and toss outa  price, and ask if it's ok.  I've actually told them 
"No, you're not charging me nearly enough and I'll feel guilty if I rob you 
like that".

Shatter <shatter@sonic.net> wrote:
  
I swear my my Pioneer DJ-1000 headphones. They rock. Beyond 
durable. Excellent sound quality (20Hz - 18k IIRC) , and have a screw on 
type 1/8 - 1/4 adapter so it never get's lost. Real nice low 
responce. Light weight. Both side full articulated for a wide variety of 
positions from full on, one ear, off the shoulder, or in hand. They slide 
all over and no position is uncomfortable. I've worn them for hours in 
paces without a monitor and never got tired of them.

About $160 @ Guitar center.

B) Weight (Pioneeds a little lighter on the head)

Still though, it was a tough call for me.  Either one, you can't go wrong.

I've always been pretty big on open disclosure.  It helpssquash rumors,=20
fantasy and assumption.  You wanna know anything -- ask me.  If I know,=20
I'll tell ya.

I know the new cameras being installed at glas kat are VERY nice.  Full=20
color, good night vision, etc.  Also use dto catch one guy who was seen=20
making a deal.  Again, the cameras wern't used at the time, they were=20
following up a call that a neighbor phoned in to the club and SFPD.  What=20
sucks is that this could cause their probation to be extended, which is=20
over in January.  ABC is notified about everything.  Anyway, the cameras=20
got VERY nice shots of the guy thatmatched the description perfectly.  They=
=20
were recgonized and until teh matter resolved, barred from entering the=20
club.  This is what it's come down to if we want to have places to go out=20
at night.

The modern casino systems are pretty amazing.  500+ computer tracked and=20
controled cameras, all with facial and MONETARY tracking.  The second is=20
the big one.

They can track how much money you drop on a table, your winnings, how much=
=20
you pull out of the ATM or get from the cashier, and how much you cash=20
in.  This is done to check to see if the dealers are pulling the overpay=20
scam.  This is pretty scarey if it were applied to all teh surveillence=20
cams all over the place.

Ever notice those traffic cams on the freeway?  Ever see one that's sitting=
=20
90degrees to the road it's watching?  I have, too many times.

The camera in the Coast Guard tower on YBI are highly sophisticated.  They=
=20
can read licent plates of moving cars on the GG bridge, no problem.  Full=20
digital jitter correction and tracking.

The cameras on the GG bridge can fully detect car speed, without the use of=
=20
rader.  It's pretty simple:  Take pictures at 10/second, then analize the=20
vehical differences to calculate the MPH based on established marked=20
distances on the bridge.  Computers have no problems tracking all cars and=
=20
on a live feed "painting" the speed over various cars as somebody=20
watches.  It's also how the auto ticketing systems work for speed violators.

Anyway...

Like the guy said, the cameras don't prevent crime, not in teh least.  They=
=20
can assist with after a crime has happened or an incident, with good=20
folowup that's pretty unbiased.  My favorite is the "No officer, I never=20
touched security, they were abusing their authority.  I was=20
co-operating."  Cop looks at camera footage of the guy not 5 minutes before=
=20
taking wild swings, and clocking on of the guys in the jaw.

I mean, I'm all for civil disobedience and fighting for right, but FFS,=20
pick your battles.  Love parade '05 we had a guy rush a gate with about=20
3lb's of weed (something close to 2 brown shopping bags).  We were under=20
direction form teh promoter, as part of his permit, not to allow any booze=
=20
or drugs into the plaza.  We performed simple bag checks.  Was anything=20
confiscated?  No.  Peopel were simply told "You either have to get rid of=20
that, or drink it outside the barracade."  Well, this guy though rushing=20
the gate and taking a swing at one of our guys was a good idea.  He was=20
handcuffed and police were called via radio to come take him off ourhands=20
(he was placed under citizens arrest, and per the law, they HAVE to be=20
released to a Police officer.  The officer is under no obligation to tak=20
ethe person to jail, but they have to take custody of the suspect.  Keep=20
this in mind when you see security arrest somebody and call the=20
cops.  Believe me, there's nothing i woudl rather do than after handcuffing=
=20
somebody who's out of line, letting them take a 15 minute breather until=20
they're cool, and cut'em loose with a "don't come around for another month"=
=20
but I can't.)

While waiting for the police the guys friends (who now had the weed)=20
started all teh typical civil crap at us, about our rights, his rights, we=
=20
can't do that, abuse of authority, blah blah blah.  Never mind the guy=20
committed Battery against security) and got his friend riled up.  The guy=20
figure dout where his friend was doing and started banging his face into=20
the pavement, over and over, and scrapeing himself.  Fortunatly, the cop=20
walke dup quietly, his friends bailed, but he kept on, so the cops got a=20
good look.  When he was pulled up, he started in with the "Look what=20
security did to me!!!  I want to file charges!"  The cops laughed.

Not the first time I've had people do that.

Funny thing is, it would have gone down like this had the guy not been a=
 jerk:

A)  You can't bring your weed in.  No I'm not checking your pockets.  guy=20
:"ok, thanks, I'll stash it"
B)  You can't bring the weed in.  Rush gate, pop security.  Security=20
arrests.  "That was dumb dude."  Cops show up.  Sec - "Ya, he rushed the=20
gate, hit me in the face."  Cop - "You wanna press charges?"  Sec - "Naw.=20
It happens."  Cop - "ok, we'll walk him down the street, cut him loose."

Seriously, that's 99% of those problems.  Security doesn't want to bust=20
anyone, and the cops don't want paperwork (in SF).

>Crobar and Spirit, have found that the security cameras do not prevent
>crime because there is no one on the other end monitoring what is going
>on. 'Our experience is they don=A2t make the clubs safer,' Mr. Bookman
>said."

>http://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/14/nyregion/14clubs.html?ex=3D1313208000&en=

>with low end CCTV cameras or from many of the typical camera placements=20
>used in practice despite the claims from BioBouncer and others that they=20
>can use existing camera installations. In my experience that doesn't work=

=20

>nightclub if installed correctly.
>

>environment, but there certainly will be other places where such systems=20
>will be deployed including eventually IMO nightclubs.  FWIW casinos have=20
>been using facial recognition for a few years to track card counters etc.=
=20
>with mixed results.  (See http://www.biometrica.com/) The technology has=20
>advanced considerably in the past few years and is now about to see=20
>widespread deployment in a number of other locations and environments=20
>including banking, retail, and entertainment venues.

>Wow...   ya, this is going REAL far off the original topic...  I'm actually
