>
>First off...  I don't know of any club that monitors the cameras
>actively.  Most go to a DVR system or...  in older cases, still to
>VHS.  You might have a manager watching something at random points, however
>typically, they are reviewed as needed, typically based on security logs,
>incident reports, or other issues.  I can also say that 99% of the time,
>they are view to make sure employee'd acted correctly, and not to keep tabs
>on a particular patron.  There are time that if somebody was a problem, eg
>weapon in club, the tapes will be played back to find out what time they
>entere dthe club, who was on door, to find out who fucked up on the
>screening/pat down.
>
>In all cases I've dealt with security footage, it's been in conjunction
>with a report, to gain a different viewpoint, or see what was missed.  I've
>never had a time where the footage was watched looking for something
>happening at the time, live.  They're always watched at a later time, be it
>an hour or several weeks later.
>
>Clubs I work in, if they even have inside cameras, they are typically on
>the bar and the registerers, and are used to make sure employee's arn't
>robbing the place.  They are also on various access points, such as
>emergancy doors, back access hallways, and such.  Because of the way they
>record, and the nightclub enviorment, recording inside a club would be
>somewhat problematic.  Don't believe me?  Feel free to tune into DNA's
>webcam live anytime you like:   Http://www.dnalounge.com  Watch for a while
>and you'll see that the crowd shots are next to impossibleto make out who's
>who.  The stage is easy enough of the lights are brough.  The bar isn't bad
>only because of constant illumination, and the front door is the easiest to
>watch.  Friends of mine in Portland have had many entertaining nights with
>beer and a computer, watching the front door camera, adding their own
>soundtrack to what they see.
>
>Again, nightclubs are not casinos.
>
>Now....  since this has diverted, and RFID's have been brought
>up...  consider this:
>
>Stores have talked about, and have already implimented things such as RFID
>dust.  When you walk in you get hit with teh dust.  This tells scanners any
>number of bits of data.  If it's incrimented with a sequential number say
>every 5 minutes, they know when you enter and leave a store.  As you walk
>around in the store, they can track movements, and see what people are
>looking for, when you browse, stop, etc.  They have talked about things
>such as active coupons and sale deals, that when you walk up, your RFID is
>read and sales are brought to your attention, to the extent that they read
>what you have already put in your basket, and make reccomendations as you
>shop around.  Hows that for Big Brother?
>
>Years back...   '93/'94 I'd have to say, I was on a voice brdige and
>somebdoy was pulling various pranks.  We called up Gail Thackery just for
>fun (see Operation Sundevil in your cyber history books).  She pointed out
>back that far that if what we had thought was bad then was nothing
>comapired to what we would be seeing with the "Club Cards" and membership
>cards like Costco.  Imagine your every item purchased front food, to
>alcohol, tobacco, foot cream, antacid, pain killers, cigarettes, etc.,
>going into variousdata bases.  Not anon shopping patterns, but right down
>to all of your personal information and Social Security number.
>
>Now, take that one step further and tie that into your credit and medical
>history.   Imagine getting a letter from your HMO saying that they are
>raising your preimiums because you have moved into a new class of at risk
>for heart disese based on the amount of red meat you've been purchasing
>over the last several years, or you are now being screened for a possible
>addition to decongestants because you have purchased more than is safe to
>use in a given time frame.  Perhaps you are ot given a job offer because
>when looking over your candidate sceening report they saw that you are an
>above average consumer of alcohol and their insuance won't cover=
 alcoholics.

> >dangrsmind@yahoo.com wrote:
> >>"A camera has no prejudice with the images it takes."
> >>
> >>This isn't really true.  In the context of a large venue's security
> >>system you usually have people monitoring at least some of the cameras
> >>and deciding when to intervene in various situations.  Since humans are
> >>involved there are clearly biases.  And some cameras are steerable or=
 can
> >>be zoomed on specific areas by these personnel.  Clubs also use hidden
> >>cameras unlike other heavily imaged places like banks.  Selective
> >>placement of hidden cameras can be a form of prejudice.
> >>
> >>It is also not true that you can't be identified and tracked if you=
 don't
> >>submit to an ID scan.  When the camera is connected to a facial
> >>recognition system the club might not know your true name, but they can
> >>still track you anonymously.  Existing systems allow the club to record
> >>when you visit, what areas of the club you prefer, potentially determine
> >>other people who you talk with, and more.  This information has value to
> >>the venue owner both for security and marketing purposes, and you can
> >>expect them to extract that value when it is economically feasible and=
 in
> >>their interest to do so.
> >>
> >>Simply by using a well placed camera and time stamp information a venue
> >>owner can link your face with a list of credit card transactions that
> >>also are time stamped.  This can all be done covertly without your
> >>cooperation or knowledge.  These features are increasingly being built
> >>into security oriented DVR (digital video recorder) platforms so they
> >>will be standard capabilities of many surveillance systems in a few
> >>years.  See for example: http://www.3vr.com
> >>
> >>And it isn't just the venue owner.  Phones are being built that have=
 face
> >>recognition capability built in, and there are services emerging that=
 are
> >>going to offer various sorts of image search and analytics to the
> >>consumer directly on their PCs and mobile devices.
> >>
> >>See also: http://www.applefritter.com/bannedbooks
> >>
> >>Like i said previously, remaining anonymous today takes work. It is no
> >>longer a given.

Subject: RE: [sfraves] Deejay Headphone Recommendations? Sony MDR v700 industry standard

This might help:

http://www.fullcompass.com/product/237383.html

Info:

Ultrasone DJ1 Pro
The Ultrasone DJ1Pro headphones are geared for professional DJ applications 
where their sealed-back construction helps to attenuate the distracting 
ambient noise coming from all those dance-crazed partiers. The accentuated 
upper frequencies of the DJ1Pro may prove especially beneficial to DJs 
seeking to keep on top of of hi-hat & cymbal cues or track their 
scratch/mixing synchronicity while working multiple turntables or mixing 
sources. Their full bass response helps to approximate the deep bass of 
dance music or hip-hop production styles. The mid-range response is just 
slightly recessed which gives the overall sound a hint of discontinuity that 
serves to emphasize the lower and upper parts of the sound spectrum. The 
seal from external noise is pretty good making these cans effective over-all 
performers and a good choice for club DJs.

An extra nice feature of the DJ1Pro is the choice of cables that are 
available with the package. A 10-foot coiled cord featuring a nifty in-line 
volume control with INDEPENDENT left/right adjustment and a stereo/mono 
switch is a major plus for DJs dialing in headphone volume on the fly or for 
listening to the mono mix with one ear. That same feature could prove useful 
for listeners who suffer some hearing loss in one ear. A 10-foot straight 
cord is also enclosed along with an extra pair of plush speed-switch 
earpads. The de rigeur 1/4" to 1/8" plug adapter is included along with a 
handy-dandy storage/carry bag for good measure.

Subject: Re: [sfraves] NRR: club security, cameras, facial recognition, and privacy (was Re: [sfraves] club contacts sought)

>From my experience with security, they're very much like the police.  There
are security personel who do their job in a professional matter, and then
there are the ones who like to abuse their power.  Please do not excise the
overused mantra it's just "a few bad apples."   There has always been a
subculture of corruption and abuse of powers from the inception of
police/security in this country, it has not ceased to exist and probably
always will.  Yes there are numerous cases of out of control, often
belligerant club/bar patrons who need to be subdued to protect other people
in the bar, but I've also seen security go well over and beyond  reasonable
use of force.  I've known quite a few bouncers, many of them have tempers,
and get off on beating someone down.  I've seen a guy taunt the security
while in line at Paradise Lounge.  Heckling the security does not give them
the right to beat your ass.  The security guard starts chasing the guy into
the intersection at 11th and Folsom, chasing him around cars, the guy makes
a break for the taxi that is already occupied by three women in the
backseat, jumps across their lap.  The security guard tries to get in as
many punches as possible while the door is open before the cabbie punches
it.  I've also seen bouncers from a number of establishments on 11th St
start to beat the crap out of someone guy for kicking the Taco stands sign
that's next to Butter.  There were at least 5 or 6 of them, they'd already
subdued the guy in a chokehold against the wall, and a few of them were
ready to wail on the kid with their maglites.  Luckily, a friend of the guy
was able to intervene before the beating could commence and was able to
convince security that he'd remove him from the area.  I could site a numbe=
r
of other stories as well and I think it's a common thing with bouncers
almost everywhere.  They are often confrontational, and use force when it
doesn't need to be used.  There are definitely some clubs who have trained
their security to be friently to its patrons, and how to manage conflicts i=
n
a proper, safe and professional manner.  We need more of that in this city,
and less vigilante cowboys working for clubs.

> controled cameras, all with facial and MONETARY tracking.  The second is
> the big one.
>
> They can track how much money you drop on a table, your winnings, how muc=
h
> you pull out of the ATM or get from the cashier, and how much you cash
> in.  This is done to check to see if the dealers are pulling the overpay
> scam.  This is pretty scarey if it were applied to all teh surveillence
> cams all over the place.
>
> Ever notice those traffic cams on the freeway?  Ever see one that's
> sitting
> 90degrees to the road it's watching?  I have, too many times.
>
> The camera in the Coast Guard tower on YBI are highly sophisticated.  The=
y
> can read licent plates of moving cars on the GG bridge, no problem.  Full
> digital jitter correction and tracking.
>
> The cameras on the GG bridge can fully detect car speed, without the use
> of
> rader.  It's pretty simple:  Take pictures at 10/second, then analize the
> vehical differences to calculate the MPH based on established marked
> distances on the bridge.  Computers have no problems tracking all cars an=
d
> on a live feed "painting" the speed over various cars as somebody
> watches.  It's also how the auto ticketing systems work for speed
> violators.
>

>

> least.  They

> folowup that's pretty unbiased.  My favorite is the "No officer, I never
> touched security, they were abusing their authority.  I was
> co-operating."  Cop looks at camera footage of the guy not 5 minutes
> before
> taking wild swings, and clocking on of the guys in the jaw.
>

> pick your battles.  Love parade '05 we had a guy rush a gate with about
> 3lb's of weed (something close to 2 brown shopping bags).  We were under
> direction form teh promoter, as part of his permit, not to allow any booz=
e
> or drugs into the plaza.  We performed simple bag checks.  Was anything
> confiscated?  No.  Peopel were simply told "You either have to get rid of
> that, or drink it outside the barracade."  Well, this guy though rushing
> the gate and taking a swing at one of our guys was a good idea.  He was
> handcuffed and police were called via radio to come take him off ourhands
> (he was placed under citizens arrest, and per the law, they HAVE to be
> released to a Police officer.  The officer is under no obligation to tak
> ethe person to jail, but they have to take custody of the suspect.  Keep
> this in mind when you see security arrest somebody and call the
> cops.  Believe me, there's nothing i woudl rather do than after
> handcuffing
> somebody who's out of line, letting them take a 15 minute breather until

> month"
> but I can't.)

> >Crobar and Spirit, have found that the security cameras do not prevent
> >crime because there is no one on the other end monitoring what is going
> >on. 'Our experience is they don=A2t make the clubs safer,' Mr. Bookman

> http://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/14/nyregion/14clubs.html?ex=3D1313208000&e=

> >
> >It is also worth noting that facial recognition doesn't work acceptably
> >with low end CCTV cameras or from many of the typical camera placements
> >used in practice despite the claims from BioBouncer and others that they
> >can use existing camera installations. In my experience that doesn't wor=
k

o
> >work and I believe would  work even in the low light environment of a
> >nightclub if installed correctly.
> >
> >We're just starting to see these technologies applied to the banking
> >environment, but there certainly will be other places where such systems
> >will be deployed including eventually IMO nightclubs.  FWIW casinos have
> >been using facial recognition for a few years to track card counters etc=

> >with mixed results.  (See http://www.biometrica.com/) The technology has
> >advanced considerably in the past few years and is now about to see
> >widespread deployment in a number of other locations and environments
> >including banking, retail, and entertainment venues.

> > >dangrsmind@yahoo.com wrote:
> > >>"A camera has no prejudice with the images it takes."
> > >>
> > >>This isn't really true.  In the context of a large venue's security
> > >>system you usually have people monitoring at least some of the camera=
s
> > >>and deciding when to intervene in various situations.  Since humans
> are
> > >>involved there are clearly biases.  And some cameras are steerable or
> can
> > >>be zoomed on specific areas by these personnel.  Clubs also use hidde=
n
> > >>cameras unlike other heavily imaged places like banks.  Selective
> > >>placement of hidden cameras can be a form of prejudice.
> > >>
> > >>It is also not true that you can't be identified and tracked if you
> don't
> > >>submit to an ID scan.  When the camera is connected to a facial
> > >>recognition system the club might not know your true name, but they
> can
> > >>still track you anonymously.  Existing systems allow the club to
> record
> > >>when you visit, what areas of the club you prefer, potentially
> determine
> > >>other people who you talk with, and more.  This information has value
> to
> > >>the venue owner both for security and marketing purposes, and you can
> > >>expect them to extract that value when it is economically feasible an=
d
> in
> > >>their interest to do so.
> > >>
> > >>Simply by using a well placed camera and time stamp information a
> venue
> > >>owner can link your face with a list of credit card transactions that
> > >>also are time stamped.  This can all be done covertly without your
> > >>cooperation or knowledge.  These features are increasingly being buil=
t
> > >>into security oriented DVR (digital video recorder) platforms so they
> > >>will be standard capabilities of many surveillance systems in a few
> > >>years.  See for example: http://www.3vr.com
> > >>
> > >>And it isn't just the venue owner.  Phones are being built that have
> face
> > >>recognition capability built in, and there are services emerging that
> are
> > >>going to offer various sorts of image search and analytics to the
> > >>consumer directly on their PCs and mobile devices.

After having one pair of Sony V700's around 5 years ago, I vouched never to
go back to em again.  They break way to easy, and quite honestly have a
really high pitched tinny sound to them when you turn them up, I always fee=
l
like I have a pair of coffee cans on my ears.  Quite honestly, I can't
believe so many dj's use them!    I'm really happy with the Sennheiser's I
bought, don't know the model off of the top of my head-  but they've lasted
me around 4 years, they were slightly damaged once when they were stepped
on, but I still use em without any noticeable discomfort.

Sony changed the design and materials used on v700 about 2 years ago. The
new ones do not crack, have a softer pad for your ear and a different cable
going from the phones to the mixer. I have had mine for about a year a half=
,
unfortunately I need to buy new ones. The new ones are spring loaded and my
roommate just stating playing and thought they were the wrong way so he
turned the ear piece until the piece snapped. Very sucky for me! But overal=
l
the new Sony's are pretty swell and if you know the right people at guitar
center they are like $90

Nick

References: <397732.55438.qm@web51507.mail.yahoo.com>	 <BAY110-F358FE2F7258B6A3AC458CC85D60@phx.gbl> <bdbe1bd30612131230p7cb4cf73hb3b6485240391a11@mail.gmail.com>
In-Reply-To: <bdbe1bd30612131230p7cb4cf73hb3b6485240391a11@mail.gmail.com>
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=windows-1252; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 8bit
X-Spam-Rating: taz3.hyperreal.org 1.6.2 0/1000/N
Subject: Re: [sfraves] Deejay Headphone Recommendations? Sony MDR v700 industry
 standard vs the V900

I cant recommend Pioneers what-so-ever. Their headphones are built like 
their mixers. Nuff said... 100% of people I know have had them loose a 
channel on them (all of them the left channel I believe).

The v700's have been upgraded as to not be so prone to cracking (per 
Sony anyways) and they are a pretty good deal. I've had my first v700s 
for five years now and they still work. Although the pads feel like 
tough leather. I haven't used them in a long while though. About three 
and a half years ago I bought a new pair of them when I saw little 
cracks in the hinges on the first ones (the new ones broke, but not by 
me). I also still have my first true deejay headphones... MDR v600's. 
These things rock and can be found for like $65 now (they were $200 
retail 7-8 years ago). I still use them as my studio headphones.

For me, playing out, I only can really recommend one headphone. The 
Technics RP-DH1200's. Technics' headphones are taking over with a lot of 
working/touring deejays the world over and for a good reason. They are 
built well and sound great. Much better than the v700s in every way. You 
can turn them up as loud as you need and they never distort (like the 
v700's do). Not as loud, or quite as accurate, as the MDR v900's but for 
deejay applications they're just as good sonically but much more usable. 
When I bought mine I bought them and the new Denon DN-HP1000 and tested 
them side by side for a few days. The Denon's went back. Even though the 
manufacture specs are essentially identical the Tech's sounded much 
better at all levels. For deejaying the RP-DH1200s are the way to go. 
There's a few deejays in Sac (you probably know well) that have had to 
borrow mine at clubs and the next time I saw them playing they were 
using their own pair of Techs! Keep the MDR v900's for the studio.

Subject: [sfraves] BSP: 1.27.07 : SuperFunkaDiculous w/ MYAGI & Greg J + tons more (Baltimore, MD)

http://www.buzzlife.com/forums/showthread.php?t=83681

On January 27th, Ground Zero invites you to get:

*~*SUPERFUNKADICULOUS*~*

with the musical stylings of:

Myagi
West / Splank! / Moneyshot / Fight Club (Toronto, CAN)

Myagi aka Sole Claw aka Andrew Mavor has shot up like a rocket over the last 
year. Representing Canada internationally, he has played from Seoul to San 
Francisco, Halifax to Brighton, Taipei to Toronto, and has become touted as 
the next major North American breaks don. Comparisons to the other big names 
of the scene seem obvious, but don't really do justice to the range of work 
Myagi has put out, as his releases have varied from hip hop big beat infused 
party breaks through to jackin house and techy big room floor fillers.

Dropping a guitar in favor of a synthesizer well before finishing high 
school, Mavor's musical journey has landed him across the board support. The 
late John Peel (the Peel Sessions) used a Myagi track to open his show. 
Front 242 have sent kudos on a track ("Sole Claw - Smartbomb") that was 
licensed to Fingerlickin for the Plump DJ's album "Saturday Night Lotion."

The string of red hot releases that followed have landed him sets on the 
BBC, the CBC and Crystal Method's Community Service and support from 
everyone from Adam Freeland and Meat Katie through to Fatboy Slim and Freddy 
Fresh. Myagi's multi-genre approach to dance music has matured into a true 
journey through b-boy and rave culture, mashing up past and present in one 
of the most high energy, pounding experiences a club could play host to. His 
shows at clubs like The Guvernment in Toronto have led to high profile gigs 
internationally, including such highlights as Fabric in London, Fusion in 
Taiwan and San Francisco's Love Parade, where Myagi played three parties in 
12 hours.

His upcoming releases include remixes for Ursula 1000 (coming out on 
Thievery Corporations label ESL), hip hop don Maestro (as in Fresh Wes), and 
a giant remix for Ricky Stone. He has two tracks licensed to JDS's "Beats N 
Bobs" compilation on Functional Breaks, more remixes in the works, and a 
release schedule that puts most labels to shame. Touring constantly, Myagi 
is one of the hardest working men in the North American dance music, and, 
with his profile rising at an extremely rapid pace he has quickly turned 
himself into a staple of the global breaks scene.

AND

Greg J
Funky Cactus / www.KidBippy.com (SF) (SPECIAL OLDSKOOL SET!!)

Greg J runs the record label Funky Cactus Recordings and has a couple of 
releases, including forthcoming remixes of DJ Shadow, but is always thought 
of as a DJ first. With over 10 years behind the decks, his experience has 
placed him in control of 2, 3, and even 4 turntables at events across the 
United States, as well as in Toronto, Paris, Madrid, and other cities around 
the world. In his hometown he is a local headliner, recently playing with 
Krafty Kuts, Dieselboy, Mixmaster Mike, DJ Rap, Goldie, DJ Q-Bert, Atomic 
Hooligan, and many others. He has been highly acclaimed by The Bassbin 
Twins, and has also been complimented by DJ's and fans from all across the 
world who know him as one of the best mixing DJs around. His latest mix CD 
titled Jet Set is currently a leader in electronic album sales on iTunes, 
and will soon be in stores everywhere. When you see him behind the decks, 
expect him to keep the crowd hype with seamless mixing, a slammin 
selection, and hyper skratching. Greg J is one turntablist not to miss.

ON THIS NIGHT, HE WILL BE DROPPING AN OLDSKOOL WAREHOUSE SET FOR YOU ALL. 
COMPLETE WITH SCRATCHING AND ALL THE USUAL AWESOMENESS. THIS IS NOT 
SOMETHING YOU WANT TO MISS AT ALL.

THAT SYSTEM MIX - mixed by Gavin Varitech

I've recently taken on the task of ripping ALL my vinyl to a hard drive 
and after a few hours the other night got really bored. Since the mixer 
was already hooked up and Soundforge already running I decided to record 
a mix... Just for me and to give to some friends.

What I didn't expect is ending up liking it this much. However since I 
did, I've converted it to MP3 and put it up on my server. I'd love to 
get some feedback from any techno or house lovers.

http://www.djvaritech.net/mixes/thatsystem_DL.mp3

Mathias Schaffhauser - "Dear Elliot"
Leif - "No Possibility"
Minimono - "ndiki"
Seuil - "Uneasy Circle"
Szeriano - "Spandiforific"
Troy Pierce - "Girl Down By The River"
Guido Schneider - "As Dry As I Can"
Anthony Collins - "Self Esteem"
Matt Star - "Balztanz_Der_Schwingungen"
Funk D'Void & Phil Kieran - "White Lice"
Bjorn Stolpmann - "The Dubfiles"
Andy Caldwell -"Warrior" (Claude VonStroke RMX)
Ark - "Lost & Soul" (Remix)
Loudon Kleer - "Sphere"
Peter Dildo - "Curly Blonde" (Experienced Clubber)
J.T.H. - "Work It"
Peace Division - "Club Therapy"
Jamie Anderson - "Arion"
Layo & bushwacka Feat... Green Velvet - "Life To Live" (Loco Dice RMX)
Brandon Plank - "Lurking In Shadow"

Enjoy a little piece of my party; System (in Sacramento) via this 
high-bitrate MP3!

Subject: [sfraves] Some excellent Xmas music done in an ambient way

------=_Part_166996_25660633.1166122579913
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=ISO-8859-1; format=flowed
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit
Content-Disposition: inline

Forward from the hyperreal ambient list:

 Hi all,

I'm pleased to announce a new mp3 work released under the Archive moniker.
Entitled "Silent Night (Shepherds Quake)", it's available for free
download now from Dark Winter:

http://www.darkwinter.com

This is a twenty-minute piece derived entirely from a brief recording of a
music box playing "Silent Night". The machine winds down; it creaks and
grinds and eventually the audio is overtaken by scrambled reiterations of
itself; it stretches and slows, speeds and warps, chimes and clangs,
sprinkles, stutters, sputters, and melts, till eventually all that's left
is a glassy ghost of its former self.

I've subtitled the piece "Shepherds Quake" to commemorate the fact that
even on the first Christmas, people in the service industry had to work.
Whatever religion you are, and especially if you're of no religion at all,
I hope you at least get the day off this year.

Enjoy!

Peas on Earth,

Mike Hallenbeck
http://www.juniorbirdman.com/archive


-- 
Steve Osteen is SlumberMachine
http://www.SlumberMachine.com

------=_Part_166996_25660633.1166122579913--

_________

WINTER SOLSTICE BEACH BONFIRE RITUAL with RECLAIMING-SAN FRANCISCO

Wednesday, December 20
Gather 3:30pm, ritual 4pm
Ocean Beach near Taraval street, SF

INTENT -- Taking the fire of the Sun into ourselves

Join us on the eve of Winter Solstice as we gather to honor the  
shortest day and longest night of the year. We honor both the time of  
darkness and the turning of the Wheel of the Year back toward the light.

Gather 3:30pm, ritual around 4pm. We'll be there rain or shine. The  
worse the weather, the earlier we start!

Please bring clean firewood  (firewood  is always welcome - no  
pallets, nails, plywood, painted or treated  wood),  warm clothes,  
food or non-alcoholic drink to share, and a towel if  you want to  
plunge. Flashlights and dry socks are also handy.

For this ritual, please also bring drums and other instruments,  
colored cloth, and other festive props.

Transit -- The scenic L-Taraval Muni train goes to Taraval and 46th,  
walk three blocks to beach.
Map -- maps.yahoo.com (Search for "Great Highway and Taraval street.")

Questions, suggestions, compliments -- email sfrpc@yahoogroups.com

For future rituals, and for locations of other Reclaiming events  
across North America and in Western Europe, visit http:// 
www.reclaiming.org

___________




apollo@speakeasy.org

MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo

Tribenet:   http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k

Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm



"No sage or savior has ever endorsed greed and gluttony as a path  
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and  
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras,  
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and  
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can  
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and  
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond  
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative  
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in  
squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of  
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will  
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"



--Apple-Mail-1-995805997--

I couldn't find v-6's anymore (aka sony mdr-7506 I think)...

So I bought the new v-500s.  Not a big fan of the boosted bass of the=20
bigger ones (600, etc) and they're too freaking heavy and they're silver,=
=20
which also sucks.  Very happy with the 500, nice tight sound not the=20
floppycock bluybbbububub of the boosted bass poop (and better for your=20
ears, high bass SPL's on closed over ear style headphones are VERY bad for=
=20
your hearing.. reproducing anything lower than 50 hz or so out of=20
heaphones is totally pointless anyway) and they're light enough to wear=20
the 2 hour commute into work, most of the day at work, and on the ride=20
home without a painful skull ridge.

And they are charcoal gray and fold up smaller.

andyw - mutorsoundsystem - saturn5.com/andy

That sucks. It has been a well known secret for sometime that the
V6'es(7506) with a ~$75 price point have better quality drivers, wider
range, and S/N then their more expensive models. Did you try Fry's? They
sometimes have them in their velvet boxed glory. I still have my V6'es whic=
h
I bought in '98, but lately I've been using my Senn 580's since they blow i=
t
away, but the Sennheiser's are not good for DJ use.

On Thu, 14 Dec 2006, Steve Osteen wrote:
-&e->That sucks. It has been a well known secret for sometime that the
-&e->V6'es(7506) with a ~$75 price point have better quality drivers, wider

The new design v500 seem to be almost the same as the old v6 model in 
every way.  On my head, they don't seem different... same presence peak in 
the freq response, same fit, same size earcups.  Couple of design 
improvements over the v-6 though, namely internal cord routing to the 
earcups rather than the "pinched my own cable oops" design of the v-6, 
less fatigueing top of head cushion thingy and it inherits the v-600's 
hinge (that last one is a mixed blessing... but seems to be well built, 
guess they learned from their mistake).

The old design v500 were total shit, had a glossier almost kinda sparkle 
black finish, had the bigger earcups, and had a plastic inner part where 
the head size adjustment is made (which invariably cracked), the new ones 
(that are good) have a marked metal band (lines with numbers 01-10), 
smaller earcups (v-6 sized) and are a darker flat grey finish.  I bought 
them at Fry's (and yes, I was looking for v6s when I bought them... the 
old reliable in the gaudy gold cardboard box with the mortuary-ready red 
velvet).  Haven't had em for very long, but I am pleasantly surprised with 
them for sure as a owner of at least 4 pairs of v-6's over a decade of 
playing techno poop for fleeing candy kids.

andyw

WHEN: SAT DEC 16. Three screenings at 6pm, 9pm and 11:50 pm.
WHAT: "The Industrial Culture Film Festvial =96 Part 1"
WHERE: Recombinant Media Labs, San Francisco www.recombinantmedia.net
WHO: Mobilization.com and Asphodel present:
$15-$23 sliding scale
A multi-part film festival celebrating prime movers of the =20
"Industrial Culture" movement, including THROBBING GRISTLE, FAKIR =20
MUSAFAR, NERVOUS GENDER. Future events will include other artists =20
from the legendary "Industrial Culture Handbook" by RE/Search =20
Publications.
* Location: Recombinant Media Labs, 763 Brannan St., SF, CA (between =20
6th and 7th st)


******************************************************************FOR =20=

IMMEDIATE =20
RELEASE*****************************************************************=20=

*
INDUSTRIAL CULTURE FILM FESTIVAL PREMIERES IN SAN FRANCISCO  WITH =20
TRANSGRESSIVE FILMS BY
THROBBING GRISTLE, FAKIR MUSAFAR, NERVOUS GENDER

Asphodel and Mobilization.com are co-presenting a special event of =20
new and archival films by prime-movers of what has become known as =20
"Industrial Culture". The first installment of this multi-part =20
festival takes place in three separate screenings:
SATURDAY DEC. 16, 2006 at 6pm, 9pm and 11:50pm at RECOMBINANT MEDIA =20
LABS in San Francisco, CA
Advanced tickets and info: http://www.mobilization.com.

Advance Premiere Screening of THROBBING GRISTLE'S First Live =20
Performance in 23 Years:
The jewel of this first event is the premiere of a new film by =20
THROBBING GRISTLE, the English inventors of "Industrial Music". The =20
film is scheduled for release next year as part of a DVD box set, and =20=

was filmed in late 2004 at the Astoria Theater in front of an invited =20=

audience of 1500 souls. This was the first live appearance by =20
THROBBING GRISTLE since their break-up in 1981.

"Recombinant Media Labs seemed like a perfect fit for this first =20
event" says Mobilization.com founder Ethan Port. "It is an intimate =20
venue, and they have an amazing state-of-the-art ultra-frequency =20
sound system that will allow us to reproduce the THROBBING GRISTLE =20
concert film in a truly 'immersive' way not possible in a traditional =20=

theater."

Sacred Sun Dance Body Suspension Ritual Shown :
Other features include portions of the film "Dances=85Sacred and =20
Profound", which focuses on FAKIR MUSAFAR, the "godfather" or =20
"patient zero" of the Modern Primitive movement. A Native American =20
"Sun Dance" body suspension ritual filmed in the early 1980s will be =20
screened. The ritual is performed with FAKIR MUSAFAR's long time =20
friend JIM WARD. Both are prime movers in popularizing and promoting =20
a vast array of body modification styles and techniques, including =20
safe, professional body piercing.

World   Premiere of Rare 1980 Video of Transgressive Post-Punks =20
NERVOUS GENDER:
The third film is a very rare live concert from 1980 by Los Angeles =20
transgressive industrial freaks NERVOUS GENDER. Like others in the =20
early Industrial movement, NERVOUS GENDER combined the raw, =20
aggressive power of punk with electronic music. The performance, =20
filmed just 3 days after they appeared on the "Live at Target" video, =20=

features 8 year old drummer Sven Pfeiffer. (Historical Note: NERVOUS =20
GENDER was one of the first bands in the L.A. punk scene with =20
hispanic and openly gay members.) NERVOUS GENDER has also just =20
released a CD from a 1979 show when the band included PHRANC, who =20
went on to a solo career identified as the all American Jewish-=20
lesbian folk singer.

Live discussions are scheduled with: NERVOUS GENDER, FAKIR MUSAFAR, =20
MONTE CAZAZZA (the co-author of the term 'Industrial Music'), V. VALE =20=

(owner of RE/Search Publications, and author of the "Industrial =20
Culture Handbook"), CHARLES NEAL (author of "Tape Delay"), and ETHAN =20
PORT (Mobilization.com owner), plus a live installation by pyro-=20
industrial artist SCOT JENERIK and F-SPACE.   Some THROBBING GRISTLE =20
members may join the panel remotely, and Genesis has proclaimed:
MONTE CAZAZZA is hereby declared my official voice by proxy and =20
WHATEVER he says about TG I agree with.


This event also marks the release of the new hardcover edition of the =20=

"Industrial Culture Handbook", originally published in the early =20
1980s. The re-pressing is a joint release by RE/Search Publications =20
and Mobilization.com, and signed copies will be available at the show.

SPONSORS: KUSF, KZSU, SF Bay Guardian, Laughing Squid

ABOUT MOBILIZATION and THE FILM FESTIVAL:
This is the first of several film screenings Mobilization will be =20
producing in 2007. Mobilization is also infamous for it's "How to =20
Destroy the Universe" festivals which combine fiery machine-art =20
(often from the Burning Man community) with essential Industrial and =20
Post-Punk artists. Past artists have included BLIXA BARGELD (of =20
EINSTURZENDE NEUBAUTEN and formerly of NICK CAVE AND THE BAD SEEDS), =20
THE LIVING JARBOE, SAVAGE REPUBLIC, MIKE WATT, THE MERMEN and F-SPACE.

LINKS: Mobilization.com,Throbbing-Gristle.com , =20
www.nervousgender.com,  www.bodyplay.com, f-space.com, =20
researchpubs.com, asphodel.com
ABOUT RECOMBINANT MEDIA LABS:
RML cultivates radical methodologies for experiential engineering; =20
exploring performative processes which expand the formal aesthetic =20
and technological boundaries of immersive installation and surround =20
cinema. The San Francisco facility contains a flexible black box =20
environment that houses a high definition multichannel audio-visual =20
system known as Surround Traffic Control. This full fidelity array =20
consists of a design specification for 10 screens in 360 degrees =20
supported by an ultra impact 16.8.2 horizontal and vertical sound =20
diffusion system scalable for all types of rectangular rooms. The RML =20=

theatre provides all international artists in residence the =20
opportunity to take their creative impulse to the furthest frontiers =20
of sonic cinematic language and present them in the formats for =20
exhibition, symposia, workshops and real-time AV concerts.

INFORMATION : www.Mobilization.com

On 12/14/06, Apollo <apollo@speakeasy.org> wrote:
> WHEN: SAT DEC 16. Three screenings at 6pm, 9pm and 11:50 pm.
> WHAT: "The Industrial Culture Film Festvial =96 Part 1"
> WHERE: Recombinant Media Labs, San Francisco www.recombinantmedia.net
> WHO: Mobilization.com and Asphodel present:
> $15-$23 sliding scale
> A multi-part film festival celebrating prime movers of the
> "Industrial Culture" movement, including THROBBING GRISTLE, FAKIR
> MUSAFAR, NERVOUS GENDER. Future events will include other artists
> from the legendary "Industrial Culture Handbook" by RE/Search
> Publications.
> * Location: Recombinant Media Labs, 763 Brannan St., SF, CA (between
> 6th and 7th st)
>
>
> ******************************************************************FOR
> IMMEDIATE
> RELEASE*****************************************************************
> *
> INDUSTRIAL CULTURE FILM FESTIVAL PREMIERES IN SAN FRANCISCO  WITH
> TRANSGRESSIVE FILMS BY
> THROBBING GRISTLE, FAKIR MUSAFAR, NERVOUS GENDER
>
> Asphodel and Mobilization.com are co-presenting a special event of
> new and archival films by prime-movers of what has become known as
> "Industrial Culture". The first installment of this multi-part
> festival takes place in three separate screenings:
> SATURDAY DEC. 16, 2006 at 6pm, 9pm and 11:50pm at RECOMBINANT MEDIA
> LABS in San Francisco, CA
> Advanced tickets and info: http://www.mobilization.com.
>
> Advance Premiere Screening of THROBBING GRISTLE'S First Live
> Performance in 23 Years:
> The jewel of this first event is the premiere of a new film by
> THROBBING GRISTLE, the English inventors of "Industrial Music". The
> film is scheduled for release next year as part of a DVD box set, and
> was filmed in late 2004 at the Astoria Theater in front of an invited
> audience of 1500 souls. This was the first live appearance by
> THROBBING GRISTLE since their break-up in 1981.
>
> "Recombinant Media Labs seemed like a perfect fit for this first
> event" says Mobilization.com founder Ethan Port. "It is an intimate
> venue, and they have an amazing state-of-the-art ultra-frequency
> sound system that will allow us to reproduce the THROBBING GRISTLE
> concert film in a truly 'immersive' way not possible in a traditional
> theater."
>
> Sacred Sun Dance Body Suspension Ritual Shown :
> Other features include portions of the film "Dances=85Sacred and
> Profound", which focuses on FAKIR MUSAFAR, the "godfather" or
> "patient zero" of the Modern Primitive movement. A Native American
> "Sun Dance" body suspension ritual filmed in the early 1980s will be
> screened. The ritual is performed with FAKIR MUSAFAR's long time
> friend JIM WARD. Both are prime movers in popularizing and promoting
> a vast array of body modification styles and techniques, including
> safe, professional body piercing.
>
> World   Premiere of Rare 1980 Video of Transgressive Post-Punks
> NERVOUS GENDER:
> The third film is a very rare live concert from 1980 by Los Angeles
> transgressive industrial freaks NERVOUS GENDER. Like others in the
> early Industrial movement, NERVOUS GENDER combined the raw,
> aggressive power of punk with electronic music. The performance,
> filmed just 3 days after they appeared on the "Live at Target" video,
> features 8 year old drummer Sven Pfeiffer. (Historical Note: NERVOUS
> GENDER was one of the first bands in the L.A. punk scene with
> hispanic and openly gay members.) NERVOUS GENDER has also just
> released a CD from a 1979 show when the band included PHRANC, who
> went on to a solo career identified as the all American Jewish-
> lesbian folk singer.
>
> Live discussions are scheduled with: NERVOUS GENDER, FAKIR MUSAFAR,
> MONTE CAZAZZA (the co-author of the term 'Industrial Music'), V. VALE
> (owner of RE/Search Publications, and author of the "Industrial
> Culture Handbook"), CHARLES NEAL (author of "Tape Delay"), and ETHAN
> PORT (Mobilization.com owner), plus a live installation by pyro-
> industrial artist SCOT JENERIK and F-SPACE.   Some THROBBING GRISTLE
> members may join the panel remotely, and Genesis has proclaimed:
> MONTE CAZAZZA is hereby declared my official voice by proxy and
> WHATEVER he says about TG I agree with.
>
>
> This event also marks the release of the new hardcover edition of the
> "Industrial Culture Handbook", originally published in the early
> 1980s. The re-pressing is a joint release by RE/Search Publications
> and Mobilization.com, and signed copies will be available at the show.
>
> SPONSORS: KUSF, KZSU, SF Bay Guardian, Laughing Squid
>
> ABOUT MOBILIZATION and THE FILM FESTIVAL:
> This is the first of several film screenings Mobilization will be
> producing in 2007. Mobilization is also infamous for it's "How to
> Destroy the Universe" festivals which combine fiery machine-art
> (often from the Burning Man community) with essential Industrial and
> Post-Punk artists. Past artists have included BLIXA BARGELD (of
> EINSTURZENDE NEUBAUTEN and formerly of NICK CAVE AND THE BAD SEEDS),
> THE LIVING JARBOE, SAVAGE REPUBLIC, MIKE WATT, THE MERMEN and F-SPACE.
>
> LINKS: Mobilization.com,Throbbing-Gristle.com ,
> www.nervousgender.com,  www.bodyplay.com, f-space.com,
> researchpubs.com, asphodel.com
> ABOUT RECOMBINANT MEDIA LABS:
> RML cultivates radical methodologies for experiential engineering;
> exploring performative processes which expand the formal aesthetic
> and technological boundaries of immersive installation and surround
> cinema. The San Francisco facility contains a flexible black box
> environment that houses a high definition multichannel audio-visual
> system known as Surround Traffic Control. This full fidelity array
> consists of a design specification for 10 screens in 360 degrees
> supported by an ultra impact 16.8.2 horizontal and vertical sound
> diffusion system scalable for all types of rectangular rooms. The RML
> theatre provides all international artists in residence the
> opportunity to take their creative impulse to the furthest frontiers
> of sonic cinematic language and present them in the formats for
> exhibition, symposia, workshops and real-time AV concerts.
>
> INFORMATION : www.Mobilization.com
>
>
> RELATED SITES:
> www.RecombinantMedia.net
>
> www.Throbbing-Gristle.com
>
> www.NervousGender.com/contents.htm
>
> Fakir Musafar:  www.bodyplay.com
>
> www.f-space.com
>
> www.researchpubs.com
>
>
>
>

	=?Windows-1252?Q?stvial_=96_Part_1=22?=

Industrial music was invented by Throbbing Gristle and Cabaret Voltaire. Not
sure what you mean by modern industrial, but Foetus and Front 242 started
about the same time that Neubaten did, and Ministry started a year later
(although they didn't sound industrial at first)

Neubaten put on one of the only shows that I've actually been scared at, as
they set fire to the stage and curtains, and put it out once the alarms went
off. I still can't believe no one was trampled! The co-headliner was Atari
Teenage Riot, who were cut short when Alec Empire attacked some idiot in the
audience who was chanting "U.S.A.!" What a show that was!

-chris

> WHEN: SAT DEC 16. Three screenings at 6pm, 9pm and 11:50 pm.
> WHAT: "The Industrial Culture Film Festvial  Part 1"
> WHERE: Recombinant Media Labs, San Francisco www.recombinantmedia.net
> WHO: Mobilization.com and Asphodel present:
> $15-$23 sliding scale
> A multi-part film festival celebrating prime movers of the
> "Industrial Culture" movement, including THROBBING GRISTLE, FAKIR
> MUSAFAR, NERVOUS GENDER. Future events will include other artists
> from the legendary "Industrial Culture Handbook" by RE/Search
> Publications.
> * Location: Recombinant Media Labs, 763 Brannan St., SF, CA (between
> 6th and 7th st)
>
>
> ******************************************************************FOR
> IMMEDIATE
> RELEASE*****************************************************************
> *
> INDUSTRIAL CULTURE FILM FESTIVAL PREMIERES IN SAN FRANCISCO  WITH
> TRANSGRESSIVE FILMS BY
> THROBBING GRISTLE, FAKIR MUSAFAR, NERVOUS GENDER
>
> Asphodel and Mobilization.com are co-presenting a special event of
> new and archival films by prime-movers of what has become known as
> "Industrial Culture". The first installment of this multi-part
> festival takes place in three separate screenings:
> SATURDAY DEC. 16, 2006 at 6pm, 9pm and 11:50pm at RECOMBINANT MEDIA
> LABS in San Francisco, CA
> Advanced tickets and info: http://www.mobilization.com.
>
> Advance Premiere Screening of THROBBING GRISTLE'S First Live
> Performance in 23 Years:
> The jewel of this first event is the premiere of a new film by
> THROBBING GRISTLE, the English inventors of "Industrial Music". The
> film is scheduled for release next year as part of a DVD box set, and
> was filmed in late 2004 at the Astoria Theater in front of an invited
> audience of 1500 souls. This was the first live appearance by
> THROBBING GRISTLE since their break-up in 1981.
>
> "Recombinant Media Labs seemed like a perfect fit for this first
> event" says Mobilization.com founder Ethan Port. "It is an intimate
> venue, and they have an amazing state-of-the-art ultra-frequency
> sound system that will allow us to reproduce the THROBBING GRISTLE
> concert film in a truly 'immersive' way not possible in a traditional
> theater."
>
> Sacred Sun Dance Body Suspension Ritual Shown :
> Other features include portions of the film "DancesSacred and
> Profound", which focuses on FAKIR MUSAFAR, the "godfather" or
> "patient zero" of the Modern Primitive movement. A Native American
> "Sun Dance" body suspension ritual filmed in the early 1980s will be
> screened. The ritual is performed with FAKIR MUSAFAR's long time
> friend JIM WARD. Both are prime movers in popularizing and promoting
> a vast array of body modification styles and techniques, including
> safe, professional body piercing.
>
> World   Premiere of Rare 1980 Video of Transgressive Post-Punks
> NERVOUS GENDER:
> The third film is a very rare live concert from 1980 by Los Angeles
> transgressive industrial freaks NERVOUS GENDER. Like others in the
> early Industrial movement, NERVOUS GENDER combined the raw,
> aggressive power of punk with electronic music. The performance,
> filmed just 3 days after they appeared on the "Live at Target" video,
> features 8 year old drummer Sven Pfeiffer. (Historical Note: NERVOUS
> GENDER was one of the first bands in the L.A. punk scene with
> hispanic and openly gay members.) NERVOUS GENDER has also just
> released a CD from a 1979 show when the band included PHRANC, who
> went on to a solo career identified as the all American Jewish-
> lesbian folk singer.
>
> Live discussions are scheduled with: NERVOUS GENDER, FAKIR MUSAFAR,
> MONTE CAZAZZA (the co-author of the term 'Industrial Music'), V. VALE
> (owner of RE/Search Publications, and author of the "Industrial
> Culture Handbook"), CHARLES NEAL (author of "Tape Delay"), and ETHAN
> PORT (Mobilization.com owner), plus a live installation by pyro-
> industrial artist SCOT JENERIK and F-SPACE.   Some THROBBING GRISTLE
> members may join the panel remotely, and Genesis has proclaimed:
> MONTE CAZAZZA is hereby declared my official voice by proxy and
> WHATEVER he says about TG I agree with.
>
>
> This event also marks the release of the new hardcover edition of the
> "Industrial Culture Handbook", originally published in the early
> 1980s. The re-pressing is a joint release by RE/Search Publications
> and Mobilization.com, and signed copies will be available at the show.
>
> SPONSORS: KUSF, KZSU, SF Bay Guardian, Laughing Squid
>
> ABOUT MOBILIZATION and THE FILM FESTIVAL:
> This is the first of several film screenings Mobilization will be
> producing in 2007. Mobilization is also infamous for it's "How to
> Destroy the Universe" festivals which combine fiery machine-art
> (often from the Burning Man community) with essential Industrial and
> Post-Punk artists. Past artists have included BLIXA BARGELD (of
> EINSTURZENDE NEUBAUTEN and formerly of NICK CAVE AND THE BAD SEEDS),
> THE LIVING JARBOE, SAVAGE REPUBLIC, MIKE WATT, THE MERMEN and F-SPACE.
>
> LINKS: Mobilization.com,Throbbing-Gristle.com ,
> www.nervousgender.com,  www.bodyplay.com, f-space.com,
> researchpubs.com, asphodel.com
> ABOUT RECOMBINANT MEDIA LABS:
> RML cultivates radical methodologies for experiential engineering;
> exploring performative processes which expand the formal aesthetic
> and technological boundaries of immersive installation and surround
> cinema. The San Francisco facility contains a flexible black box
> environment that houses a high definition multichannel audio-visual
> system known as Surround Traffic Control. This full fidelity array
> consists of a design specification for 10 screens in 360 degrees
> supported by an ultra impact 16.8.2 horizontal and vertical sound
> diffusion system scalable for all types of rectangular rooms. The RML
> theatre provides all international artists in residence the
> opportunity to take their creative impulse to the furthest frontiers
> of sonic cinematic language and present them in the formats for
> exhibition, symposia, workshops and real-time AV concerts.
>

>> new and archival films by prime-movers of what has become known as
>> "Industrial Culture". The first installment of this multi-part
>> festival takes place in three separate screenings:
>> SATURDAY DEC. 16, 2006 at 6pm, 9pm and 11:50pm at RECOMBINANT MEDIA
>> LABS in San Francisco, CA
>> Advanced tickets and info: http://www.mobilization.com.
>>
>> Advance Premiere Screening of THROBBING GRISTLE'S First Live
>> Performance in 23 Years:
>> The jewel of this first event is the premiere of a new film by
>> THROBBING GRISTLE, the English inventors of "Industrial Music". The
>> film is scheduled for release next year as part of a DVD box set, and
>> was filmed in late 2004 at the Astoria Theater in front of an invited
>> audience of 1500 souls. This was the first live appearance by
>> THROBBING GRISTLE since their break-up in 1981.
>>
>> "Recombinant Media Labs seemed like a perfect fit for this first
>> event" says Mobilization.com founder Ethan Port. "It is an intimate
>> venue, and they have an amazing state-of-the-art ultra-frequency
>> sound system that will allow us to reproduce the THROBBING GRISTLE
>> concert film in a truly 'immersive' way not possible in a traditional
>> theater."
>>
>> Sacred Sun Dance Body Suspension Ritual Shown :
>> Other features include portions of the film "Dances=85Sacred and
>> Profound", which focuses on FAKIR MUSAFAR, the "godfather" or
>> "patient zero" of the Modern Primitive movement. A Native American
>> "Sun Dance" body suspension ritual filmed in the early 1980s will be
>> screened. The ritual is performed with FAKIR MUSAFAR's long time
>> friend JIM WARD. Both are prime movers in popularizing and promoting
>> a vast array of body modification styles and techniques, including
>> safe, professional body piercing.
>>
>> World   Premiere of Rare 1980 Video of Transgressive Post-Punks
>> NERVOUS GENDER:
>> The third film is a very rare live concert from 1980 by Los Angeles
>> transgressive industrial freaks NERVOUS GENDER. Like others in the
>> early Industrial movement, NERVOUS GENDER combined the raw,
>> aggressive power of punk with electronic music. The performance,
>> filmed just 3 days after they appeared on the "Live at Target" video,
>> features 8 year old drummer Sven Pfeiffer. (Historical Note: NERVOUS
>> GENDER was one of the first bands in the L.A. punk scene with
>> hispanic and openly gay members.) NERVOUS GENDER has also just
>> released a CD from a 1979 show when the band included PHRANC, who
>> went on to a solo career identified as the all American Jewish-
>> lesbian folk singer.
>>
>> Live discussions are scheduled with: NERVOUS GENDER, FAKIR MUSAFAR,
>> MONTE CAZAZZA (the co-author of the term 'Industrial Music'), V. VALE
>> (owner of RE/Search Publications, and author of the "Industrial
>> Culture Handbook"), CHARLES NEAL (author of "Tape Delay"), and ETHAN
>> PORT (Mobilization.com owner), plus a live installation by pyro-
>> industrial artist SCOT JENERIK and F-SPACE.   Some THROBBING GRISTLE
>> members may join the panel remotely, and Genesis has proclaimed:
>> MONTE CAZAZZA is hereby declared my official voice by proxy and
>> WHATEVER he says about TG I agree with.
>>
>>
>> This event also marks the release of the new hardcover edition of the
>> "Industrial Culture Handbook", originally published in the early
>> 1980s. The re-pressing is a joint release by RE/Search Publications
>> and Mobilization.com, and signed copies will be available at the =20
>> show.
>>
>> SPONSORS: KUSF, KZSU, SF Bay Guardian, Laughing Squid
>>
>> ABOUT MOBILIZATION and THE FILM FESTIVAL:
>> This is the first of several film screenings Mobilization will be
>> producing in 2007. Mobilization is also infamous for it's "How to
>> Destroy the Universe" festivals which combine fiery machine-art
>> (often from the Burning Man community) with essential Industrial and
>> Post-Punk artists. Past artists have included BLIXA BARGELD (of
>> EINSTURZENDE NEUBAUTEN and formerly of NICK CAVE AND THE BAD SEEDS),
>> THE LIVING JARBOE, SAVAGE REPUBLIC, MIKE WATT, THE MERMEN and F-=20
>> SPACE.
>>
>> LINKS: Mobilization.com,Throbbing-Gristle.com ,
>> www.nervousgender.com,  www.bodyplay.com, f-space.com,
>> researchpubs.com, asphodel.com
>> ABOUT RECOMBINANT MEDIA LABS:
>> RML cultivates radical methodologies for experiential engineering;
>> exploring performative processes which expand the formal aesthetic
>> and technological boundaries of immersive installation and surround
>> cinema. The San Francisco facility contains a flexible black box
>> environment that houses a high definition multichannel audio-visual
>> system known as Surround Traffic Control. This full fidelity array
>> consists of a design specification for 10 screens in 360 degrees
>> supported by an ultra impact 16.8.2 horizontal and vertical sound
>> diffusion system scalable for all types of rectangular rooms. The RML
>> theatre provides all international artists in residence the
>> opportunity to take their creative impulse to the furthest frontiers
>> of sonic cinematic language and present them in the formats for
>> exhibition, symposia, workshops and real-time AV concerts.
>>
>> INFORMATION : www.Mobilization.com
>>
>>
>> RELATED SITES:
>> www.RecombinantMedia.net

>>
>> Fakir Musafar:  www.bodyplay.com

marketh thine calendars!


Saturday, January 6th

[ K O N T R O L ]

minimal techno + avant house
every first Saturday at the Endup


featuring from Berlin, Germany:

=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D>  DANIEL BELL aka DBX  <=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D

Accelerate . 7th City . Plus 8 . M-nus . Perlon

The master of minimal returns!  When Dan Bell takes
the decks, it's over. You will dance. No one can move a
dancefloor like this man. Everything there is to be said
has already been said. Just be there, and prepare for
one of the greatest nights out you've experienced in SF.


and from Ann Arbor, Michigan:

=3D=3D> MATTHEW DEAR aka AUDION - LIVE! <=3D=3D

Spectral Sound . Plus 8 . M-nus . Perlon

If you've heard Matthew's amazing DJ sets, you've only
heard half the story.  This month, alongside one of his
personal heroes, Mr. Dear will dip into his entire arsenal
of original material to rip SF a new one. Seriously, you
do not want to miss this one.  ...As if you would!


plus special guest from Winnipeg, Canada:

=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D>  S=DCZ  <=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D

Archipel . Unfoundsound . De'fchild

We always knew that S=FCz had great taste in music, but
recently we've discovered the girl can lay down some
tracks, too!  Her "Montreal Jones" mix was one of our
hands down favorites of 2005, and we are supremely
excited to showcase her talent at a proper SF getdown.


with resident DJs:

NIKOLA BAYTALA ( robsoul . junior boys own . s.w.a.t. )
CRAIG KUNA  ( concept sf . esdjco )
SAMMY D  ( classic . dirtybird . utensil )
ALLAND BYALLO  ( liebe detail . floppy funk )

BIO: DANIEL BELL

Born in Sacramento, California, Daniel Bell grew up outside of Toronto,
Canada, and then moved to Detroit where he collaborated with Richie Hawtin
as Cybersonik for three years on Plus 8 Records. In 1991, he started his ow=
n
label, Accelerate, on which he released his influential releases as DBX.
Based on nearby Chicago "track" records, he reduced that sound further into
funky, streamlined grooves. The formula proved to be successful and helped
launch a new aesthetic in techno and house music known as "minimal".

With the overwhelming success of his "Losing Control" single in 1994, Danie=
l
set up 7th City Distribution in order to assist smaller Midwest labels to
get distribution in overseas markets. He also created three new labels - 7t=
h
City, Elevate and Harmonie Park. In 2000, he relocated to Berlin, Germany,
and released his first mix CD, "The Button-Down Mind of Daniel Bell", on
Tresor Records, followed in 2003 by "The Button-Down Mind Strikes Back!" He
since has produced a series of remixes for a diverse range of artists,
includng John Tejada, Pantytec, Akufen and John Thomas. He has spent the
last 3 years traveling and DJing around the world.


Daniel Bell's website:
http://www.daniel-bell.com/

Daniel Bell's discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Daniel%20Bell

Daniel Bell interview on InTheMix.com:
http://www.inthemix.com.au/features/23336/

_________________________________________________


BIO: MATTHEW DEAR

You could throw around generous descriptors and any number of genre-locking
terms =96 minimal house, acid techno, electronic pop =96 but you'd still fa=
il to
get to the center of Matthew Dear. With releases under no fewer than three
aliases, including False (M_NUS), Jabberjaw (Perlon), and Audion (Spectral
Sound), the Texas native has earned his international status over the cours=
e
of a decade, from getting his bearings on the DJ decks as a teenager to
flooring sold-out crowds at venues like Fabric and releasing
universally-praised original recordings.

After meeting Ghostly founder Sam Valenti at a house party in the late 90s,
Dear eventually produced the A-Side for the label's first 12" release Hands
Up for Detroit. Since becoming the flagship artist for the
dancefloor-oriented Spectral Sound offshoot, Dear has created the albums
Leave Luck to Heaven and Backstroke under his birth name, as well as a
series of singles and the Suckfish LP as Audion, all the while building a
reputation for some of the most evolved live electronic sets ever crafted.
He'll still tell you that his greatest pleasure is a quiet day of fishing,
but with plans for a new Audion single (split with Ellen Allien, no less)
and another full-length under his proper name, it's clear that Dear has no
intention of slowing down anytime soon.


AUDION website:
http://www.suckfish.org/

Matthew Dear website:
http://www.matthewdear.com/

Matthew Dear's discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Matthew%20Dear

On June 4, 1963, an unknown Presidential decree, Executive Order
#11110 was signed with the authority to strip the Federal Reserve of
its power to lend money to the United States Government and interests.
   With the stroke of a pen, Kennedy would have put the Fed out of
business.  The November assassination quieted the production of the
new currency, however the Executive Order still stands, unrepealed.

Another good thing about Yahoo Music Unlimited is that it has a very
Native American approach to music and ownership. Why bother owning
music, there isn't any need to actually own it, just listen to it when
you want by on demand streaming. Why waste time and disk space by
building up and organizing an MP3 collection? I'm not pro Yahoo or
anything, I just discovered this and find it completely cool.

needed this underground sooo bad!!!  I met alota Awesome People who Wow..

OK.. so i was like talkin' to Anti Tim on AIM most the whole day that day
& like i mean... we always make plans to hang out & kick it now that he's
in teh EB & we've never yet... so we decided to ride up to Space Gallery
together... I spoke w/ another friend in Berk to meet me @ BART & walk w/
me to Tim's.. well.. we walked 1/2 way there together through Campus like
talking & stuff...

Got to Tim's, ate some Turkey Soup, we went to Skills to see all teh Candy
Ravers goin to ummmm... Trippindicular... that was soooo CUTE!!!

So after a we went to the City, had a mad adventure looking for parking,
lol, saw the line for this 92.7 party in some venue (which i later found
out my Homegirl Vix was there), then we made it to space gallery & yeah!!

It was such a Dope night!!  OK.. Music 1st... like the 1st 2 DJs played a
whole bunch of yummy breaks, electro Clash, i think some house, but it was
all mash up stylee & I Loved it!! Then Jay Walker's band performed like
this Really Awesome Rock music!  I kinda lost 1 of my earplugs right when
they came on.. so i kinda was like outside 1/2 the time listening to them
from out there or like down stairs on the sofa.. i mean.. i wanted to be
in there like the whole time.. but my ears are like trained to have
earplugs in @ all loud times... BUt man.. they were Awesome!!!  Ummm..
there was this one song.. like the 2nd from last that they performed... it
was my fave from their whoel set!

Then George went on.. OK.. this guy is a one man fuckin' band!  He had his
drum machine, lap top, keyboard, & guitar in hand & a mic to sing in!!!
OK... his Vocals, YUM!!  I LOVE HIS SINGING!!  He's gotten realle like
more cleaner i guess w/ his vocals & he sings pretty high too!!  YUM!! 
The songs he performed from the album, HELLO 2DAY!!!  So Dope!!!  I
mean... the music was kinda louder than the singing in some songs when he
did them live.. i dunno if that was intentional, but ooh man...  YUM YUM!!
 My Fave song was Come Again Another Day where Lyds sang!  I mean... I
Loved it!  I mean, there's also another song where Lyds sings on & duets
w/ George, I don't remember the name of it, but I Love that song too!!  I
also Love Love Love Love My World!!! OK.. CD review later!!!

After that, AndyW spun like a well... lol.. Hello 2Day.. like 10 minutes
of Ghetto Tech before i guess the bar owner wanted to shut down early, so
yeah... we all pretty much got kicked out @ 1:20ish...

But yeah... it was a family filled event... i mean.. 1/2 the other family
that was suppose to be there was Probably @ Anu for Folded, but it was
still fun!  Yeah man.. it was just Groovy to like see people who i Love w/
all my heart & catch up hardcore w/ them! :) :) <3<3<3<3

Oh yeah.. Space Gallery is a cute, small lil hole in the wall :)  LoL..
OK.. the bathroom, there's only 1, & lol.. the lock on the door don't even
work.. i dunno why i brought that up, but it was just memorable for some
reason.. anywaze.. like there's 2 small hang out areas down stairs & a
bar.. then up stairs there like it's like a kinda big floor w/ a hole in
the middle for the stairs (& a few places to hide if you were like playing
hide n go seek)...

So there was mini after shindig @ Casa Horhay & Lyds... lol.. ok.. lol..
like i needed somewhere to chill b4 bart opened.... so i went there!  LIke
it was mad Crazy!! I met this like Fresh from Italy Dude, ummmm, Antonio i
think his name was... Oh my gosh.. he was sooo Awesome to hang out w/ as
well as all the other new people i met that night @ the Casa!  Oh yeah...
i even saw Chazz Gold (are you still on here Chazz?) when i went to the
pizza place & his GF lives in the same building... he even came over for
like a minute to borrow condems!!  LOLOLMAO!  Andy got to spin his
GhettoTech set plus like all the other yummy music he had in his record
pack thingie that night :)  So fun!!  lol.. by like 5AM... "the 3 Late
Night Warriors" were still up, Me, George, & Andy & I think i sobered up
enough to take the journey home!

Oh yeah... @ the Bus Stop on Haight, i met a lawyer looking for a job! 
That was Dope!!  I forgot her name, but her BF, Paul, works w/ George!

OK.. it's kinda late now & I'll be sure to type up my personal review fo
the CD when i wakey up:)

Love U guys!!!  NIght Night!

> Subject:
> Re: [sfraves] ravezooka
> From:
> dangrsmind@yahoo.com
> Date:
> Fri, 15 Dec 2006 15:59:32 -0800 (PST)
> To:
> sfraves@hyperreal.org
>
> To:
> sfraves@hyperreal.org
>
>
> I believe Hawkwind invented the musical weapon.
>  
> Sonic Attack
>  
> In case of Sonic Attack on your district,
> follow these rules.....
> If you are making love, it is imperative to bring all bodies to orgasm simultaneously
> Do not waste time blocking your ears
> Do not waste time seeking a soundproof shelter
> Try to get as far away from the sonic source as possible, but do not panic.....
> Use your wheels, it is what they are for
> Small babies may be placed inside the special cocoons, which should be left if possible, in a shelter
> Do not attempt to use your own limbs
> If no wheels are available, metal, not organic, limbs should be employed whenever practical.....
> Remember, in the case of Sonic Attack,
> Survival does mean every man for himself
> Statistically more people survive
> if they think only of themselves
> Do not attempt to rescue friends,
> relatives, or loved ones.
> You have only a few seconds to escape
> Use those seconds sensibly or you will inevitably die
> Do not panic
> Think only of yourselves....
> These are the first signs of Sonic Attack:
> You will notice small objects, such as ornaments, oscillating.
> You will notice a vibration in your diaphragm
> You will hear a distant hissing in your ears
> You will feel dizzy
> You will feel the need to vomit
> There will be bleeding from orifices
> There will be an ache in the pelvic region
> You may be subject to fits of hysterical shouting,
> or even laughter
> These are all sign of imminent Sonic destruction
> Your only real protection is flight
> If you are less than ten years old,
> then remain in your shelter and use your cocoon
> But remember: You can help no-one else,
> No-one else,
> No-one else...... 
>
> -- Hawkwind
>  
> http://www.last.fm/music/Hawkwind/_/Sonic+Attack
>  
> I used to listen to Hawkwind a lot back in the 70s. 
>  
> There's also a book:  http://www.amazon.com/Time-Hawklords-Michael-Butterworth/dp/189652205X
>
> I like your cupid's bow idea too!
>  
> Peace,
>  
> Peter

actually i think there was a company in california that developed a non 
lethal weapon  designed for shooting sound at an enemy target and doing 
everything short of bursting their eardrums. it has been deployed 
currently in iraq at border crossings. i think there was also some audio 
research into focusing audio waves for advertising. the frequencies were 
engineered to vibrate the bones in your head much like the lollipop toy 
radio that broadcasts into your head via your jaw bone and inner ear 
bones when you bite down on it.

just imagine going into a natural history museum and having 
predetermined computerized speech enter your head about the happy life 
of the giant african land snail (which you have to see to believe 
http://www.geocities.com/Heartland/Valley/6210/) as you walk past and it 
fades. or imagine if you will, a bunch of crazy weird people out in the 
park in broad daylight dancing to a pa system driven by a focused beam 
of sound into their brains.

respects,
sean.

totally suggested! :)

:Code TV News Present:
Out of the box

WHEN?  December 22nd, 11PM-6AM

WHY? Tis the season to get your Groovy on!

WHAT?  Electro Clash, Techno, Jungle, Breaks, 2 Step, Grime, House

WHAT ELSE?  Were working w/ a local food bank and collecting canned goods
the whole night to help out those less fortunate!

Also, a portion of the proceeds will go to the Kim family RIP James!

No BYOB Please!

City, SF, CA

Subject: [sfraves] Oh yeah, The White Pinecone CD review

Oooh oh ohoh.. before i forget... I just rememered from the afterparty,
Andy dropped Jack & Diane by by John Cougar during the after party & i
remember like singing to like whoever during that song in the kitchen & it
was just Dope!!  There was also this record he dropped w/ just noise that
didn't make any sense, but it was fun & we just laughed :)  I <3 Andy's
REcords!

OK.. so here's my Review of George's CD :)

When i heard the songs performed live... i kinda formulated in my head
that i;d descibed them as like Retro Rock, Electronic, Mondo Heavy on the
Funky, Pop-ish, kinda songs w/ an edge, well... 'cause when people passed
by or like the people from the bar next door  asked what kinda music was
playing, that's what I told them!

When i 1st listened to the whole album when i got home, yeah man... I
kinda like felt like i was listening to some kinda J Pop music... like
Pitzicatto 5, Samurai Sorcerers, Fanybutt, ummmm... Phantom Radio is
another one & oh gosh.. there's this other group from Japan that i really
used to Love from back in the day where like 1 of their songs about about
sex as food... or something like that... but yeah... if George ever like
finds a distributer in Japan, i know this album would hit #1 there :)

The White Pinecone is a Really Groovy Album & I"m sooo proud of you Big G
for all the hardwork you put in this!  I do look foward to hearing more of
your solo work in this realm of music & see what comes out next from your
Musical Hat! YAAAY! :)  Oh yeah.. & the singing... like said before... SO
DOPE!!!  I mean.. G's Vocals are so Awesome, strong, powerful, & his
falcetto is even pretty Strong too!  Love it Love It Love It!

OK.. yeah.. i know.. i gotta stop w/ the insomniac postings 'cause it's
like almost 4:30.. but yeah... my brain's still on the weekend hours right
now & Oh My Goodness man, i reeeeeeally gotta change that!

But yeah SFR.. if you haven't gotten your copy yet, ummm... i think you
just go to the website www.thewhitepincone.com or like
www.dinnerpartyrecords.com & purchase it there :)  You so will not be
Sorry!  Oh Yeah.. like when i listen to music, whatever Genre, I always
imagine like it being Movie Sountrack Music & yeah.. this CD has alota
those songs for me like if i were watching a movie & yeah...

OK... The White PineCone get's my Hello 2Day stamp of Yummy... ok,
infomercial over.. nightnight SFR :)
-- 
Take Care <3

> > I believe Hawkwind invented the musical weapon.

> > Sonic Attack
> >
> > In case of Sonic Attack on your district,
> > follow these rules.....
> > If you are making love, it is imperative to bring all bodies to orgasm simultaneously
> > Do not waste time blocking your ears
> > Do not waste time seeking a soundproof shelter
> > Try to get as far away from the sonic source as possible, but do not panic.....
> > Use your wheels, it is what they are for
> > Small babies may be placed inside the special cocoons, which should be left if possible, in a shelter
> > Do not attempt to use your own limbs
> > If no wheels are available, metal, not organic, limbs should be employed whenever practical.....
> > Remember, in the case of Sonic Attack,
> > Survival does mean every man for himself
> > Statistically more people survive
> > if they think only of themselves
> > Do not attempt to rescue friends,
> > relatives, or loved ones.
> > You have only a few seconds to escape
> > Use those seconds sensibly or you will inevitably die
> > Do not panic
> > Think only of yourselves....
> > These are the first signs of Sonic Attack:
> > You will notice small objects, such as ornaments, oscillating.
> > You will notice a vibration in your diaphragm
> > You will hear a distant hissing in your ears
> > You will feel dizzy
> > You will feel the need to vomit
> > There will be bleeding from orifices
> > There will be an ache in the pelvic region
> > You may be subject to fits of hysterical shouting,
> > or even laughter
> > These are all sign of imminent Sonic destruction
> > Your only real protection is flight
> > If you are less than ten years old,
> > then remain in your shelter and use your cocoon
> > But remember: You can help no-one else,
> > No-one else,
> > No-one else......
> >

Saturday, January 6th

[ K O N T R O L ]

minimal techno + avant house
every first Saturday at the Endup


featuring from Berlin, Germany:

=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D>  DANIEL BELL aka DBX  <=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D

Accelerate . 7th City . Plus 8 . M-nus . Perlon

The master of minimal returns!  When Dan Bell takes
the decks, it's over. You will dance. No one can move a
dancefloor like this man. Everything there is to be said
has already been said. Just be there, and prepare for
one of the greatest nights out you've experienced in SF.


and from Ann Arbor, Michigan:

=3D=3D> MATTHEW DEAR aka AUDION - LIVE! <=3D=3D

Spectral Sound . Plus 8 . M-nus . Perlon

If you've heard Matthew's amazing DJ sets, you've only
heard half the story.  This month, alongside one of his
personal heroes, Mr. Dear will dip into his entire arsenal
of original material to rip SF a new one. Seriously, you
do not want to miss this one.  ...As if you would!


plus special guest from Winnipeg, Canada:

=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D>  S=DCZ  <=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D=3D

Archipel . Unfoundsound . De'fchild

We always knew that S=FCz had great taste in music, but
recently we've discovered the girl can lay down some
tracks, too!  Her "Montreal Jones" mix was one of our
hands down favorites of 2005, and we are supremely
excited to showcase her talent at a proper SF getdown.


with resident DJs:

NIKOLA BAYTALA ( robsoul . junior boys own . s.w.a.t. )
CRAIG KUNA  ( concept sf . esdjco )
SAMMY D  ( classic . dirtybird . utensil )
ALLAND BYALLO  ( liebe detail . floppy funk )

BIO: DANIEL BELL

Born in Sacramento, California, Daniel Bell grew up outside of Toronto,
Canada, and then moved to Detroit where he collaborated with Richie Hawtin
as Cybersonik for three years on Plus 8 Records. In 1991, he started his ow=
n
label, Accelerate, on which he released his influential releases as DBX.
Based on nearby Chicago "track" records, he reduced that sound further into
funky, streamlined grooves. The formula proved to be successful and helped
launch a new aesthetic in techno and house music known as "minimal".

With the overwhelming success of his "Losing Control" single in 1994, Danie=
l
set up 7th City Distribution in order to assist smaller Midwest labels to
get distribution in overseas markets. He also created three new labels - 7t=
h
City, Elevate and Harmonie Park. In 2000, he relocated to Berlin, Germany,
and released his first mix CD, "The Button-Down Mind of Daniel Bell", on
Tresor Records, followed in 2003 by "The Button-Down Mind Strikes Back!" He
since has produced a series of remixes for a diverse range of artists,
includng John Tejada, Pantytec, Akufen and John Thomas. He has spent the
last 3 years traveling and DJing around the world.


Daniel Bell's website:
http://www.daniel-bell.com/

Daniel Bell's discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Daniel%20Bell

Daniel Bell interview on InTheMix.com:
http://www.inthemix.com.au/features/23336/

_________________________________________________


BIO: MATTHEW DEAR

You could throw around generous descriptors and any number of genre-locking
terms =96 minimal house, acid techno, electronic pop =96 but you'd still fa=
il to
get to the center of Matthew Dear. With releases under no fewer than three
aliases, including False (M_NUS), Jabberjaw (Perlon), and Audion (Spectral
Sound), the Texas native has earned his international status over the cours=
e
of a decade, from getting his bearings on the DJ decks as a teenager to
flooring sold-out crowds at venues like Fabric and releasing
universally-praised original recordings.

After meeting Ghostly founder Sam Valenti at a house party in the late 90s,
Dear eventually produced the A-Side for the label's first 12" release Hands
Up for Detroit. Since becoming the flagship artist for the
dancefloor-oriented Spectral Sound offshoot, Dear has created the albums
Leave Luck to Heaven and Backstroke under his birth name, as well as a
series of singles and the Suckfish LP as Audion, all the while building a
reputation for some of the most evolved live electronic sets ever crafted.
He'll still tell you that his greatest pleasure is a quiet day of fishing,
but with plans for a new Audion single (split with Ellen Allien, no less)
and another full-length under his proper name, it's clear that Dear has no
intention of slowing down anytime soon.


AUDION website:
http://www.suckfish.org/

Matthew Dear website:
http://www.matthewdear.com/

Matthew Dear's discography:
http://www.discogs.com/artist/Matthew%20Dear

Subject: [sfraves] Please be careful out there

I know you hear this a lot, but I'm specifically talking to the women -- 
please watch yourselves.  Violent crime has been in the increase lately, 
especially this month.  I had to deal with an AWD (Assault with deadly) a 
few weeks ago and less than half a block away there was a BRR (Battery, 
Robbery and Rape) of a close friend.

She's a touch girl.  Hits harder than most guys, tough, very tom boy.  She 
woke up in SF Gen not knowing how she got there with doctors applying a 
rape kit to her.

Please, travel in numbers, and get somebody (preferably large and male) to 
walk you to your car.  If you don't know any and you're near a club, ask 
security of somebody could walk you.  If you parked down the block, give a 
cabbie $5 to drive you to your car and wait for you to get in and lock the 
door.

Carry your pepper spray and if you're inclined, a taser.  If you don't know 
how to use these, ask somebody that knows to teach you.

Do not yell "HELP".  Yell "FIRE" something along those lines.

Rememeber that despite what liberal media PCist's will tell you, a rape 
victem is not more rightious than a woman standing over her assailent 
holding a smoking gun.

Be smart, think ahead, keep friends close and a guy or two that will watch 
your back.  If you've had a few, get a cab.  A towed car is cheaper than 
medical bills.

Just please, be careful out there.  I don't want to read about any more 
victems in SF this year.  I've dealt with too many already.




Shatter

http://www.sonic.net/~shatter
Y!: Shatter707  ICQ: 8953718  MSN & AIM:  TheRealShatter
