Wow...the source.  He is the funk in my soul.  God speed.


Legendary singer James Brown dies at 73

By GREG BLUESTEIN, Associated Press Writer 12 minutes ago

ATLANTA -
James Brown, the dynamic, pompadoured "Godfather of Soul," whose  
rasping vocals and revolutionary rhythms made him a founder of rap,  
funk and disco as well, died early Monday, his agent said. He was 73.

Brown was hospitalized with pneumonia at Emory Crawford Long Hospital  
on Sunday and died around 1:45 a.m. Monday, said his agent, Frank  
Copsidas of Intrigue Music. Longtime friend Charles Bobbit was by his  
side, he said.

Copsidas said the cause of death was uncertain. "We really don't know  
at this point what he died of," he said.

Along with Elvis Presley, Bob Dylan and a handful of others, Brown  
was one of the major musical influences of the past 50 years. At  
least one generation idolized him, and sometimes openly copied him.  
His rapid-footed dancing inspired Mick Jagger and Michael Jackson  
among others. Songs such as
David Bowie's "Fame," Prince's "Kiss," George Clinton's "Atomic Dog"  
and Sly and the Family Stone's "Sing a Simple Song" were clearly  
based on Brown's rhythms and vocal style.

If Brown's claim to the invention of soul can be challenged by fans  
of Ray Charles and Sam Cooke, then his rights to the genres of rap,  
disco and funk are beyond question. He was to rhythm and dance music  
what Dylan was to lyrics: the unchallenged popular innovator.

"James presented obviously the best grooves," rapper Chuck D of  
Public Enemy once told The Associated Press. "To this day, there has  
been no one near as funky. No one's coming even close."

continued:   http://news.yahoo.com/s/ap/obit_brown







apollo@speakeasy.org

MySpace:  http://www.myspace.com/DJApollo

Tribenet:   http://people.tribe.net/djapollo2k

Moksha Tribe:  www.mokshatribe.org

House Music 101:  http://livingart.com/raving/articles/housemusic101.htm



"No sage or savior has ever endorsed greed and gluttony as a path  
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and  
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras,  
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and  
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can  
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and  
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond  
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative  
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in  
squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of  
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will  
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"

>From: Gavin Varitech <gavin@djvaritech.net>
>To: sfraves@hyperreal.org
>Subject: Re: [sfraves] Deejay Headphone Recommendations? Sony MDR v700 
>industry standard vs the V900
>Date: Wed, 13 Dec 2006 13:16:22 -0800
>
>I cant recommend Pioneers what-so-ever. Their headphones are built like 
>their mixers. Nuff said... 100% of people I know have had them loose a 
>channel on them (all of them the left channel I believe).
>
>The v700's have been upgraded as to not be so prone to cracking (per Sony 
>anyways) and they are a pretty good deal. I've had my first v700s for five 
>years now and they still work. Although the pads feel like tough leather. I 
>haven't used them in a long while though. About three and a half years ago 
>I bought a new pair of them when I saw little cracks in the hinges on the 
>first ones (the new ones broke, but not by me). I also still have my first 
>true deejay headphones... MDR v600's. These things rock and can be found 
>for like $65 now (they were $200 retail 7-8 years ago). I still use them as 
>my studio headphones.
>
>For me, playing out, I only can really recommend one headphone. The 
>Technics RP-DH1200's. Technics' headphones are taking over with a lot of 
>working/touring deejays the world over and for a good reason. They are 
>built well and sound great. Much better than the v700s in every way. You 
>can turn them up as loud as you need and they never distort (like the 
>v700's do). Not as loud, or quite as accurate, as the MDR v900's but for 
>deejay applications they're just as good sonically but much more usable. 
>When I bought mine I bought them and the new Denon DN-HP1000 and tested 
>them side by side for a few days. The Denon's went back. Even though the 
>manufacture specs are essentially identical the Tech's sounded much better 
>at all levels. For deejaying the RP-DH1200s are the way to go. There's a 
>few deejays in Sac (you probably know well) that have had to borrow mine at 
>clubs and the next time I saw them playing they were using their own pair 
>of Techs! Keep the MDR v900's for the studio.
>
>

Subject: Re: [sfraves] Genius Of Love

-------------------------------1167152450
Content-Type: text/plain; charset="US-ASCII"
Content-Transfer-Encoding: 7bit

I always loved that song. For those who don't know, it's by the Tom Tom Club, 
who were a spin-off of Talking Heads, featuring the wife-husband team of Tina 
Weymouth on bass and Chris Frantz on drums. Genius of Love was a huge hit 
around 1983 and was very influential. 

The best part of singing along was the part that goes "James Brown ... James 
Brown ..." going up and down in pitch all funky sounding. And the part about 
getting out of jail was apropos, since James served time on occasion. 

Saw James Brown at the Circle Star Theater in San Carlos a long, long time 
ago... about 1982. Doubt many of you have heard of it, but it was a theater in 
the round with a slowly spinning stage. Those who paid the most money got the 
performer facing them more of the time. Kinda a rip-off tactic, but it was THE 
place in the Bay Area to see the soul and R&B performers at the time. 

-------------------------------1167152450--

Nonsense.=0A=0AMaybe the average futurist's house will have 100 computers "=
mostly networked to each other, and to the Web", but I doubt that too.=0A=
=0AMy prediction: In three years the average house in the U.S. will have le=
ss than 10 internetworked computers including both machines only on a home =
LAN and those connected to the broader Internet or another out of home netw=
ork.  =0A=0AMy house is fairly advanced as these things go and we have exac=
tly six such computers (including two web enabled cellphones) today.   Ther=
e is no conceivable scenario under which we will multiply this number by a =
factor of ten in the next three years, even if we wanted to for some reason=
 I don't fathom exactly at the moment.=0A=0AIn general people tend to over =
estimate the changes that will occur within 2-3 years and underestimate the=
 changes that will occur in ten years or more.  Time will tell about this s=
pecific prediction I guess, but the problem with making short term predicti=
ons is that it is way too easy to check with reality to see the results. Ke=
ep the prediction horizon out more than ten years and no one will remember =
your prediction long enough to check whether you were right or not.=0A=0AOf=
 course it also depends on your definitions of "computer", "networked" and =
"the Web"=0A=0ARegards,=0A=0APeter=0A=0AP.S. Most futurists make prediction=
s that are easy to make but much harder to check.  I once started a thing c=
alled the "Short Term Futurists Society" as a revolt against this approach,=
 in which we tried to make only predictions with time horizons less than on=
e year.  These predictions are easy to check, but hard to make.  Try it you=
rself; fun for the whole family!=0A=0A----- Original Message ----=0AFrom: D=

Subject: [sfraves] WHY DJ's are booked... and the categories where they exist....

Imma bbreak it down for everyone. Consider the Gospel
of Eric regarding DJ's:

There are many categories of DJ's to be hired. Some
have talent, other do not. Below you will find who and
why DJ's are booked.

1) Big Name Draw.
This is usually an out-of-towner who is hot at the
moment. They may or may not be excellent DJ's, but are
booked because people know their name, and it is
currently cool to say you are going to see them.

2) Local Headliners.
This is a category of DJ's that has spent years in the
scene, and their name promotes the party. These Dj's
are usually good, and have been playing for so long
that everyone knows their name, and enjoys supporting
them.

3) Local DJ's in general.
a) This person is a great DJ, the promoter enjoys
their music, and thinks they will fit into the scheme
of the event. They will probably say nice things about
the event to those they see on the street, will tell
their friends, and support through bbasic internet
calendar postings and the like.
b) This person is a consumate promoter of the events
they play at. You care less about whether they are
good and more about the promotion you get from them.
c) This person is really a promoter. You book them to
keep them from throwing a party against you in order
to save the numbers. They usually suck, but through
massive flyering for their own events have gotten
their name so saturated in people minds that they now
have a draw. Think Dyloot, Ron Reeser, etc....
d) This person is just a nice guy. Probably not the
best DJ, but not the worst. Does basic promotion, but
is more of a pity booking because you like them and
know how much they appreciate the booking.

4) Newcomers.
This DJ probably has very little skill, but is so
excited about playing out that they help promote, get
their friends to come and PAY for the event, help
setup, and basically become an event evangelist. They
open in thh SideShow Bob room. This person goes on to
become a promoter/DJ (3c), or actually becomes a DJ
after years of practice.

Where do you fit in? Some people are combos of the
above.

Eric

Subject: Re: [sfraves] WHY DJ's are booked... and the categories where they exist....

You forgot:

5) Producers. A person that mostly creates his/her own music and looks
as DJ'ing as a way to promote and share their music. They may or may
not be a good DJ and most likely spend so much time in the studio that
they have great ears, but poor marketing skills.


On 12/28/06, Eric Spire <ericspire@yahoo.com> wrote:
> Imma bbreak it down for everyone. Consider the Gospel
> of Eric regarding DJ's:
>
> There are many categories of DJ's to be hired. Some
> have talent, other do not. Below you will find who and
> why DJ's are booked.
>
> 1) Big Name Draw.
> This is usually an out-of-towner who is hot at the
> moment. They may or may not be excellent DJ's, but are
> booked because people know their name, and it is
> currently cool to say you are going to see them.
>
> 2) Local Headliners.
> This is a category of DJ's that has spent years in the
> scene, and their name promotes the party. These Dj's
> are usually good, and have been playing for so long
> that everyone knows their name, and enjoys supporting
> them.
>
> 3) Local DJ's in general.
> a) This person is a great DJ, the promoter enjoys
> their music, and thinks they will fit into the scheme
> of the event. They will probably say nice things about
> the event to those they see on the street, will tell
> their friends, and support through bbasic internet
> calendar postings and the like.
> b) This person is a consumate promoter of the events
> they play at. You care less about whether they are
> good and more about the promotion you get from them.
> c) This person is really a promoter. You book them to
> keep them from throwing a party against you in order
> to save the numbers. They usually suck, but through
> massive flyering for their own events have gotten
> their name so saturated in people minds that they now
> have a draw. Think Dyloot, Ron Reeser, etc....
> d) This person is just a nice guy. Probably not the
> best DJ, but not the worst. Does basic promotion, but
> is more of a pity booking because you like them and
> know how much they appreciate the booking.
>
> 4) Newcomers.
> This DJ probably has very little skill, but is so
> excited about playing out that they help promote, get
> their friends to come and PAY for the event, help
> setup, and basically become an event evangelist. They
> open in thh SideShow Bob room. This person goes on to
> become a promoter/DJ (3c), or actually becomes a DJ
> after years of practice.
>
> Where do you fit in? Some people are combos of the
> above.
>
> Eric
>

As far as deejaying goes this person belongs along side 3B. Massive 
respect to those that write their own music, but for those that can't 
play it well in a live setting, leave it to those that can.

No respect to those promoters that book producers for deejay sets, 
simply for the name value, even if they've never ever heard a demo mixed 
of this person before. (a practice most often found in Drum & Bass circles)

On 28 December 2006, Gavin Varitech wrote:

> As far as deejaying goes this person belongs along side 3B. Massive respect 
> to those that write their own music, but for those that can't play it well in 
> a live setting, leave it to those that can.
>
> No respect to those promoters that book producers for deejay sets, simply for

<sarcasm>But just set them up with a Traktor DJ Studio setup and have it 
beatmatch for them!</sarcasm>

In seriousness.  This has become a problem in searching out DJ talent to 
book for the radio show.  Seems like anymore, 90+ % of the demo mixes 
out there are tweaked together (nothing implied there) by this or 
similar software.  So it doesn't represent at all what someone might 
sound like when given a rig with 1200's and CDJ's.  And we're not even 
mentioning all the other post production tricks (I think AndyW mentioned 
in an earlier email about providing said service to a number of other 
DJs in the past.  Speaking of, can he be coaxed into another discussion 
about DJ wizardry?)

I agree on teh self promotion...

let me elaborate (yes, theres something I have in mind but I'm not naming 
names)

All other guests, talent, performers, and such are always listed, and 
pushed on the billing, as well as the promoters themselves, however the 
DJ's are never mentioned, even though that's about 85% of the 
entertainment, booze being the exception.  Even some gal who's gonna walk 
on stage naked nobody has ever heard of get's more billing.

Depending on who you book, you can get some great results.

irst time I had Mubali come in for a set he gave me a nice surpise:

"I just finished up a few tracks this morning, got them mastered and burnt 
off.  I'll spin them tonight, first time ever.  I think they'll like it."

That right there is just wicked cool.  He would have done live/PA with his 
rig but his laptop had become a craptop so he burnt all his back catalog 
off onto cd and mixed up his stuff.

>not be a good DJ and most likely spend so much time in the studio that
>they have great ears, but poor marketing skills.

New Years Eve 2006-7

bday was a state secret:)

As you get older, you find that often the wheat, disentangling itself  
from the chaff, comes out to meet you.  The friends I've made here on  
sfraves over the years have been the best, most thoughtful and  
loving.  I'm so grateful having you in my life.

on the dance floor much and that means I've been unable to see many  
of you.  Miss ya'.  I hope the new year bring rebirth and  the  
opportunity to share life with my friends once more.

Much love,

"No sage or savior has ever endorsed greed and gluttony as a path  
toward social justice or personal fulfillment.  These sane and  
enlightened people come to us from all cultures and all eras,  
sometimes knowing of each other but more often not.  Socrates and  
Jesus, Lao Tzu and Tolstoi, Gandhi and Martin Buber -- no one can  
find in their lives and words a jot of support for a political and  
economic regime that encourages the acquisition of wealth far beyond  
what is needed for the necessaries -- or even the restorative  
pleasures -- of life while consigning the masses to live and work in  
squalor."
-Stephen J. Fortunato, Associate Justice, Rhode Island Supreme Court.

"Music is prophecy, its style and economic organization are ahead of  
the rest of society. It makes audible the new world that will  
gradually become visible."
-Jacques Attali in his seminal text "Noise"
